<HEADLINE> India Welcomes Verdict in Atlantique Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- India Wednesday welcomed a
verdict of the International Court of Justice (ICJ) which rejected
Pakistan's plea for 16 million U.S. dollars in damages from New
Delhi for the shooting down of its military combat aircraft
Atlantique on August 10 last year, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Through its comments, the ICJ has vindicated India's stand that
the Simla Agreement and the Lahore Declaration are the very
cornerstone of Indo-Pak relations, the PTI quoted an Indian
Foreign Office spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the ICJ's decision to uphold India's submission
that the court had no jurisdiction in the matter, the spokesman
said India welcomed the court's observations that the two
neighbors should settle their disputes through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"India stands committed to dialogue and calls on Pakistan to
create the proper environment for such a dialogue through
cessation of cross-border terrorism and the abandonment of hostile
propaganda," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
