<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Unidentified assailants Wednesday hurled grenades
and fired semi-automatic weapons at Australian troops serving with
the United Nations in East Timor, the Australian Defense Force (
ADF) said.
</P>
<P>
"There were no Australian casualties," an ADF spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The troops were at a fortified U.N. post 50 kilometers north of
the town of Maliana at Aidabasalala near East Timor's border with
Indonesian West Timor when the attack occurred after midnight. (
Australia-Timor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak had ordered his
aides to prepare for a plan to build border fence along the future
border between Israel and the Palestinians, Israel's Ha'aretz
daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Peace Directorate in Barak's Office will take the lead to
organize the plan work, with the Israel Defense Forces, the police,
the office of Coordinator of Government Activities in the (
Occupied) Territories, and the ministries of Finance, Transport
and Regional Cooperation jointly participating in, the report said.
(Israel-Palestinian-Borderline)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- In a bid to calm down the situation in Indonesia's
restive province of North Maluku, more troops will be sent to the
area, Defense Minister Juwono Sudarsono said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"If you ask me about 100 percent of security situation in North
Maluku islands, I will say that it is impossible to provide
security guarantee 100 percent there. Everything is very limited.
Number of our security personnel is limited as well as our fund,"
he told reporters commenting on the renewed communal bloodshed in
North Maluku province which killed at least 152 people on Monday.
(Indonesia-Troops-N.Maluku)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- There are signs from Fiji Wednesday night that the
hostage crisis may soon be over, Australia's Special Broadcasting
Service (SBS) TV reported.
</P>
<P>
The SBS quoted sources close to the negotiations between the
military government and coup leader George Speight as saying both
sides will sign an agreement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The TV report said that the agreement will finalize
arrangements for the hostages to be freed. (Australia-Fiji)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- At least two people were seriously injured on
Wednesday in an explosion hitting a Catholic area in Belfast,
capital of Northern Ireland, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
The blast occurred at 1.30 p.m. (1230 GMT) in the Ballymurphy
area of Belfast and it is unclear what caused the explosion.
</P>
<P>
The two injured persons, aged 29 and 39, were taken to hospital.
(N.Ireland-Explosion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Leaders of the countries of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) on Wednesday called for preserving the
1972 Soviet-U.S. Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) treaty to keep
global strategic stability.
</P>
<P>
The CIS urged more efforts to preserve the treaty "through its
strict and full compliance," said a statement adopted at the end
of the summit in Moscow. (CIS-Summit-ABM) 
</P>
</TEXT>
