<HEADLINE> Palestinian Police Ban Hezbollah Leader's Phone Address </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian police Wednesday banned a
phone address to be given by the leader of Lebanese Hezbollah
guerrillas to a rally staged by the Palestinian Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) in the West Bank town of Jenin.
</P>
<P>
The police threatened to disperse the rally, held in
commemoration of the Prophet's birthday and Israel's May 24
withdrawal from south Lebanon, if Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah,
secretary-general of Hezbollah, addressed it on the phone.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday evening, the Palestinian police decided to repatriate
Nasrallah's family members from the Shojai'ya district in Gaza,
under the request by local headmen to prevent the recurrence of
clashes.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Director of Gaza Strip Police General Ghazi al-Jibali,
the Palestinian daily Al-Quds reported on Wednesday that 15 of
Nasrallah family members who lived in Shojai'ya would be moved to
another place in Gaza to prevent "further clashes."
</P>
<P>
The family is threatened with revenge after some of its members
murdered members of other families, Jibali noted.
</P>
<P>
After the completion of Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon on
May 24, Nasrallah urged the Palestinians to resume armed resistance
to end Israeli occupation of the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic developments in south Lebanon encouraged Hamas,
which opposes the Middle East peace process, to adopt the line of
Hezbollah to continue armed struggle against Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
