<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Spies Not to Be Executed: Iranian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian judiciary official
said here on Wednesday that the 13 Iranian Jews accused of spying
for Israel will not be sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
Those accused of spying for Israel will not be sentenced to
execution if they are not proved to be Mohareb (person in fight
against God), said Husseinali Amiri, head of the Justice Department
of the southern Fars Province, where the accused are under trial.
</P>
<P>
The official added that so far no Moharebeh (fighting against
God) allegations have been lodged against those involved in the
espionage, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the sentences will be issued at the latest by June 30
in proportion with the effects left by the actions carried out by
the spies within their espionage ring.
</P>
<P>
The trial of the 13 Jews by a revolutionary court in the
southern province opened on April 13. So far nine of the suspects
have reportedly admitted having connections with Israel's security
service.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Jews were arrested more than a year ago along with eight
Muslims accused of the same crimes. There have been speculations
that the accused Jews might be sentenced to death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
