<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100GMT, Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak had ordered his
aides to prepare for a plan to build border fence along the future
border between Israel and the Palestinians, Israel's Ha'aretz daily
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Peace Directorate in Barak's Office will take the lead to
organize the plan work, with the Israel Defense Forces (IDF), the
police, the office of Coordinator of Government Activities in the
(Occupied) Territories, and the ministries of Finance, Transport
and Regional Cooperation jointly participating in, the report said.
(BC-Israel-Palestinians-Border Fence)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The United Nations will continue pushing the Middle
East peace process forward and work together with countries in the
region to implement the Security Council Resolutions, said visiting
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after meeting with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, Annan said,"We will continue the efforts to implement
the resolutions 242 and 338...and work together with the
international community to push the peace process forward based on
the formula of land for peace."
</P>
<P>
"We set for peace and work for peace and hope all countries in
he region will work together for peace," Annan said.(BC-Annan-Peace
Process)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Wednesday
that he intends to engage in a continuous and fundamental dialogue
with the Jewish settlers in the West Bank and Gaza, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue is the continuation of a series of meetings between
Barak and leaders of the Council of Jewish Communities of the West
Bank, which is called Judea and Samaria by the Jews according to
the biblical tradition, and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Settlers in the West Bank and Gaza have been staging frequent
demonstrations outside Barak's residence in Jerusalem to protest
Barak's reported plan to transfer over 90 percent of the West Bank
to the Palestinians. (BC-Israel-Barak-Settlers)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's leftist party Meretz decided Wednesday to
quit Prime Minister Ehud Barak's coalition government in what it
called an effort to further Barak's peacemaking with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Three Meretz cabinet ministers will tender their resignations to
Barak later on Wednesday after the party's 10 Knesset (parliament)
members met and made the decision earlier, according to Israel
Television.
</P>
<P>
Meretz's decision may improve Barak's chances to save his
floundering government from a deepening crisis caused by defection
of the biggest coalition partner, the ultra-orthodox Shas party,
which demanded more funds for its ill-managed school system and
legalization of its radio stations. (BC-Israel-Meretz-Coalition)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 0621-52FFF Burundi Peace Agreement May Be Signed in July: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- A peace agreement to end the
long- running civil war in Burundi may be signed by all the
warring parties early next month, said Judge Mark Bomani, leader
of the mediation team for the Burundi peace process here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace facilitator and former South African
president Nelson Mandela is to present a final draft compromise
agreement to the 19 Burundi delegations scheduled to meet in July
in the northern town of Arusha, Tanzania, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The facilitation team will meet next week to revise the draft
compromise text before Mandela meets with the 19 delegations,"
Bomani told local news reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We are right on course and everything is going as planned," he
said, expressing his high hopes that the 81-year-old Mandela may
finally make a breakthrough in the 23-month old talks.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not say whether the armed rebels and the
Burundi government have made any vows to sign the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The Hutu rebels have demanded for 51 percent representation in
the army and control of the government, but Mandela was proposing
a 49-49 representation for both Tutsis and Hutu ethnic groups and
a 2 percent representation for the Twa ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
Burundi has an ethnic composition of 85 percent Hutu, 14
percent Tutsi and 1 percent Twa.
</P>
<P>
According to Bomani, a committee of the peace talks, Committee
Five on Implementation and Guarantees, is currently at a meeting
in Arusha in preparation for the next round of talks.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Arusha said that during the week-long meeting,
Committee Five would deliberate on how to integrate the armed
rebel groups into a new national defense force.
</P>
<P>
Repatriation of hundreds of thousands of Burundian refugees
currently being sheltered in refugee camps in Tanzania would be
another topic, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Heads of the 19 delegations would also deliberate on security
of exiled Burundian leaders and refugees upon their arrival in
Burundi after the signing of a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The civil war in the tiny central African country has killed
more than 200,000 people, displaced more than 1 million others and
confined several hundreds of thousands in "regroupment camps".
</P>
<P>
The war started when the first democratically elected Hutu
president Melchior Ndadaye was murdered by Tutsi soldiers in 1983.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Deploys Troops at Diplomatic Enclave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Liberia deployed anti-terrorist
troops at the diplomatic enclave in Monrovia on Wednesday with
concerns raising among foreign diplomats over the state of
security in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor told a press conference in
his office that the move was prompted by "some friendly western
intelligence sources".
</P>
<P>
"That diplomatic enclave contains Americans, French, British
and major diplomatic embassies. We have a duty to protect them,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Taylor confirmed that his government had advised British
nationals and none- governmental organizations to suspend working
in certain regions of Liberia because of "some anti-British
sentiments being harbored by some individuals".
</P>
<P>
The development came after Britain proposed the European Union
(EU) withhold a 47 million U.S. dollar aid package to Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Britain is reported to have presented intelligence materials to
the EU foreign ministers alleging Taylor's support for the rebels
of the Revolutionary United Front in neighboring Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Taylor has denied any links with the rebels other than those
sanctioned by the sub-regional body, the Economic Community of
West African States, which sent intervention force to restore the
elected Sierra Leone President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
"We regret this (withholding of aid) very much. We do believe
that it is inhumane for the British to do this," Taylor lamented
at Wednesday' s press conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
