<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Stresses Need for Aiding World's Poorest Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
stressed on Thursday that developed countries should continue to
provide aid to the poorest countries and again rejected the U.S.
doctrine of "trade, not aid" for Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the magazine "Choice" to be published by
the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), Chirac said that
aid for development "remains indispensable for all the countries
still deprived of access to international financial investment."
</P>
<P>
The content of the interview was issued on Thursday by the
Elysee presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
Chirac regretted that some countries think that economic growth
and trade are sufficient to resolve the problems of under-
development and great poverty in the world.
</P>
<P>
``Trade, not aid, this is what some people have repeated here
and there, while the situation of underdevelopment continues to
expand, whose results are that dozens of countries are simply
excluded from development,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The interview was given one week from the U.N. ``Week of
Development'' which will start on June 29 and one month from the
Group of Eight (G8) summit to be held in Okinawa, Japan.
</P>
<P>
``It is evident that to go out of the situation of
underdevelopment, the most underprivileged should be helped to
overcome their handicap at the beginning. This is the role of
public aid for development,'' said Chirac. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Calls on DRC to Reopen Mediator's Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Thursday called on the Government of the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) to reopen the Kinshasa-based office of the Facilitator
of the National Inter-Congolese.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was contained in a statement read to the press by
the president of the Security Council, Jean-David Levitte of
France, at the end of the closed Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Council deplored the lack of cooperation
of the Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo with the
Facilitator of the National Inter-Congolese Dialogue designated
with the assistance of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
including the recent closure of the office of the Facilitator,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"They called on the Government of the Democratic Republic of
the Congo to reaffirm its full commitment to the National Dialogue
which constitutes a central element of the Lusaka Agreement," the
statement said. "They called for the reopening of the office of
the Facilitator."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council met Thursday behind closed doors to be
briefed by the U.N. Secretariat on the latest development in the
DRC, including the situation in the northeastern town of Kisangani,
where Rwandan and Ugandan clashed two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Council were deeply concerned at the
information that all forces and armed groups have not yet
completed their withdrawal from Kisangani," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"They reiterated their demand that the Congolese armed
opposition and other armed groups immediately and completely
withdraw from Kisangani, and called on all parties to the Cease-
fire Agreement to respect the demilitarization of the city and its
environs," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in the DRC province of Equator, the Security
Council "called on all parties to cease hostilities throughout the
territory of the DRC and to cooperate fully with" the U.N. mission
in the DRC, known as MONUC, the statement said. "They called on
all parties to implement fully all provisions of the Lusaka
Agreement and relevant Security Council resolutions."
</P>
<P>
Beginning on July 10, 1999, warring parties signed the Lusaka
accord in a bid to end the many-sided conflicts in the central
African country, formerly called Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe supports the DRC Government,
headed by President Laurent Kabila, in fighting against rebels,
backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said in Kinshasa Wednesday that he was shutting down the
office of the Facilitator, Ketumile Masire, who is a former
president of Botswana.
</P>
<P>
The Facilitator's office was sealed and his staff dispersed,
Kabila said.
</P>
<P>
The Kabila Government earlier said that it has no longer any
confidence in Masire, the OAU-appointed Facilitator, and asked the
OAU to re-appoint a new and neutral facilitator. However, the
Security Council has since asked the Kinshasa Government to fully
cooperate with Masire.
</P>
<P>
The fighting in Kisangani resulted in the death of more than
600 civilians and more than 3,000 were wounded. The shelling of
Kisangani also destroyed the premises of the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) in Kinshasa and wounded United Nations
staff members.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Council deplored these events," the
statement said. "They called on all parties to facilitator the
delivery of humanitarian aid." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
