<HEADLINE> Rwanda Accused of Tarnishing Uganda's Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Thursday accused Rwanda of
tarnishing the name of its army and the country by displaying
Ugandan soldiers captured during the six-day fighting between
Rwandan and Ugandan forces in northern Congolese city of Kisangani
in early June.
</P>
<P>
James Wapakabulo, chairman of National Coordination Committee
on the Region, told a press conference that as part of the
demilitarization plan for Kisangani, Ugandan forces "lent" 216
officers and soldiers to the U.N. Observer team in Congo (MONUC)
as an interim measure for security arrangements of Kisangani
pending arrival of the U.N. forces.
</P>
<P>
Some of the soldiers were missing during the attack by Rwandan
army two weeks ago, said Wapakabulo, adding "MONUC has been asked
to account for their where-about.
</P>
<P>
"Since these matters involved MONUC, it had been agreed that
the accounting for the soldiers of the Uganda People's Defence
Forces (UPDF) be handled quietly behind the scenes and the process
has been on going," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate the government of Rwanda has chosen to go
public, and it is our view that is intended to tarnish the name of
the UPDF and the country as a whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
The forces of the two former allies have left Kisangani under
the supervision of the MONUC following the latest fighting in the
city.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops, which back rival rebel factions
fighting against the Democratic Republic of the Congo President
Laurent Kabila, started to shell each other on June 5 in
Kisangani. The six-day fighting killed over 200 civilians and
wounded more than 1,000 others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
