<HEADLINE> WFP Urges More Attention to Kenyan Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
Thursday appealed to the international community for more food aid
to drought- stricken Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya has appealed for 150,000 tons of food aid for the next
six months, up to now donors have indicated to provide only 20 to
25 percent of that amount," Manuel Silva, the WFP Regional
Humanitarian Coordinator for the drought, told a press conference
in the Kenyan capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
It is "very dry" in northern Kenya and pastoralists are forced
to move further north with their cattle into Ethiopia to get
better pasture, he said after winding up his five-nation tour,
which took him to Ethiopia, Somalia, Eritrea, Djibouti and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kenya has not got much attention from the mass
media, Silva noted.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged drought in the Horn of Africa is affecting about
10 million Ethiopians, 2.2 million Kenyans, 750,000 Somalis,
335,000 Eritreans and 10,000 Djiboutis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
