<HEADLINE> Bashar's Presidential Candidacy to Be Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A special committee will be formed
to study Syrian ruling Baath party's nomination of Bashar al-Assad,
the second son of late President Hafez al-Assad, for president,
said the country's parliament speaker Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The committee, to be formed in the Sunday session of the
People's Council (parliament), will group representatives from the
ruling Baath party, other parties and independents, Speaker Abdel
Kader Kaddura announced.
</P>
<P>
Kaddura told a press conference that the committee will present
its report to the parliament for debate and vote on Monday, and
parliament members will fix the date for a nationwide presidential
referendum on Bashar's presidential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
The referendum was likely to be held a week after the parliament
accepts the Baath party's nomination of Bashar, said the speaker.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Bashar was brought up in the family of a
veteran Arab politician, and struggled with other members of the
Baath party in a way that made him well qualified for leading the
country.
</P>
<P>
Kaddura said that the leadership of Baath party will hold a
meeting to assign tasks to each members and elect a secretary to
take care of its day-to-day affairs.
</P>
<P>
Twelve of its 21 members of the leadership are new faces.
Kaddura said that bringing new blood into the Baath leadership is
an important indicator of the development and evolution of the
party.
</P>
<P>
The Baath party elected Bashar as its secretary general and
nominated him for the presidency on Tuesday. Earlier, Bashar had
been promoted to the rank of general and declared commander of
Syria's armed forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
