<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Occupation of Northern Cyprus an Anachronism: Cyprus Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus government spokesman
Michalis Papapetrou said here Thursday Turkey must understand that
the continuing Turkish occupation of Cyprus' northern areas is an
anachronism.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou made the remarks as Turkish President Ahmet Necdet
Sezer started a two-day visit to the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
area in northern Cyprus at the invitation of Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining the Turkish occupation and the absence of a
solution in Cyprus, which run contrary to international law and
order, are an anachronism," Papapetrou said.
</P>
<P>
This, he pointed out, is also "against the interests of the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities."
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou said this is the message the Cyprus government wants
to send to the Turkish leadership.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then Turkey has maintained some 35,000 troops there with
the claimed aim of protecting the Turkish Cypriot minority.
</P>
<P>
In 1983 Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a breakaway
republic which is only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
According to local media, President Sezer, accompanied by State
Minister Sukru Sina Gurel and Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, arrived
in northern Cyprus at midday Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
