<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Involvement in Failed Bomb Attack on Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Hamid Reza Asefi on Thursday denied an Iraqi allegation that Tehran
is behind a failed bomb attack on Baghdad early this month.
</P>
<P>
Asefi said the Islamic Republic of Iran has not had any
involvement in the alleged bomb attack on Baghdad and strongly
rejects such a claim by Iraqi officials, the Iranian state
television reported.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Iraqi officials not to blame others for their
internal problems.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad on Thursday issued a statement claiming that four men,
including an Iranian intelligence officer, were killed in Baghdad
early this month when they were planning to launch a bomb attack.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the four were preparing a car to be used as a
rocket launcher when it accidentally exploded and killed them.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi television on Wednesday night showed footage of charred
bodies and a photo of Iranian Intelligence officer Hussein
Karamati, identified by the security office as the organizer of the
attack.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has all pieces of evidence to prove that the Iranian
intelligence agencies are involved in the planning and preparation
of such a disgraceful act, and reserves the right to retaliate
against those who attack its people, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq, who fought a bloody war in 1980-88, accused each
other in recent months of launching mortar attacks and sabotage
operations. Both Tehran and Baghdad host opposition groups of the
other.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Iranian Intelligence Ministry said on Thursday
seven members of the Iraq-based Iranian opposition Mujaheddin Khalq
Organization (MKO) were killed and several others injured recently
in the western border provinces.
</P>
<P>
In a statement broadcast by the state television, the ministry
said the MKO launched three cross-border operations but were
defeated by Iranian armed forces and people.
</P>
<P>
During the clashes, an Iranian was also killed, the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, a famous political-military group which fought against
the former Iranian shah regime, was outlawed in 1981 and fled into
Iraq due to sharp differences with the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, labeled by Iran as a "terrorist group," has launched a
series of cross-border attacks inside Iran in recent years,
including assassinating senior Iranian officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
