<HEADLINE> France to Propose Sanctions on Financial Delinquencies at G8 Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- France will propose sanctions
against the countries which refuse to cooperate in fighting
financial delinquencies, such as money laundering, at the Group of
Eight (G8) summit to be held in July in Okinawa, Japan.
</P>
<P>
French Finance Minister Laurent Fabius said on Thursday that
France would do its best to make the G8 summit adopt such measures,
and will host on October 17 a meeting of finance ministers,
interior ministers and justice ministers of European countries on
the measures against tax havens sheltering financial criminal
activities.
</P>
<P>
``We are engaged for several years in the fight against money
laundering and we will do our best to have sanctions against those
countries which don't respect the normal international rules,''
said Fabius.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Financial Action Against Money Laundering
published on Thursday a list of 15 countries which refuse to
cooperate in the fight against money laundering and 14 other
countries which little cooperate.
</P>
<P>
The Paris-based group, which is membered by 26 industrialized
countries and is affiliated to the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD), said that on the list are
Israel, the Philippines, Liechtenstein, Lebanon, Russia, the
Bahamas, Cayman Islands, Cook Islands, the Dominican Republic,
Marshall Islands, Nauru Niue, Panama, St. Christopher and Nevis,
St. Vincent and Grenada.
</P>
<P>
Fabius said that financial sanctions to be proposed by France
could go as far as cutting financial relations with the countries
on ``the black list.''
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a French parliament mission of information on
financial crimes Wednesday published a report accusing Monaco of
serving as an offshore center for money-laundering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
