<HEADLINE> UK Manufacturing Export Orders Continue to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 22 (Xinhua) - UK manufacturing exports continued
to fall in June, with orders from overseas hitting their lowest
level for a year.
</P>
<P>
Output expectations remained negative in the month after having
been positive in the nine months leading up to May, according to
the Confederation of British Industry's latest monthly survey of
industrial trends.
</P>
<P>
The CBI said 48 percent of manufacturers reported that their
export order books were below normal against only 9 percent
enjoying better than normal demand.
</P>
<P>
"Exporters are continuing to suffer from the strength of
sterling, despite the easing of the exchange rate over the past
month," said CBI director general Digby Jones.
</P>
<P>
"Export orders cannot be regained in just a few weeks... many
companies still regard the current rate against the euro as
uncompetitive," he said.
</P>
<P>
The CBI said manufacturers also had a gloomy outlook on the
volume of output over the next four months, with expectations
falling to the lowest level since March 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
