<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New High-capacity Mini Hard Drive to Be Introduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A mew mini hard drive with a
storage capacity of a billion bytes of information will be
commercially introduced this September, IBM announced this week.
</P>
<P>
The tiny Microdrive, which is the size of a book of matches, is
a milestone in the evolution of magnetic storage, IBM executives
said, because it surpasses the same one-gigabyte barrier the
company's original refrigerator-sized hard drive surmounted in the
1980's.
</P>
<P>
The first 340-megabyte Microdrive introduced a year ago had a
storage density of 5.04 billion bits a square inch, while the
current drive has increased that density to 15.2 billion bits a
square inch.
</P>
<P>
The higher density means the tiny new drive is within 10
percent of the most advanced IBM storage products now on the
market, the company said. A one-gigabyte drive could hold up to 1,
000 high-resolution photographs, a thousand 200-page novels, or
nearly 10 hours of high-quality digital audio music.
</P>
<P>
IBM expected about one-third of the market for the new drives
to be as storage devices for digital cameras. Another third of the
market would come as backup and data-transfer media for notebook
and desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
But in the future the Microdrive will be put into hand-held
computing devices like persona digital assistants and advanced
digital cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the new hard drive has the ability to resist a
1500-G shock, that is equivalent to a drop from a normal office
desk onto a medium-thickness carpet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N.Says HIV/AIDS Epidemic Shifting From Cities to Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a new publication entitled Sustainable Agriculture/Rural
Development and Vulnerability to the AIDS Epidemic, FAO and UNAIDS
called upon governments to pay more attention to the real burden
of HIV/AIDS on local communities and to ensure that rural
development also aims at combating the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
"HIV/AIDS is not only a health but also a development problem,"
FAO and UNAIDS said.
</P>
<P>
The report says it is urgent to address rural HIV prevention
and care needs. Though HIV prevalence is rising in rural areas,
the infrastructure needed for prevention programs -- counseling
and testing, condom availability and AIDS information -- is less
developed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, health facilities are often inadequate in rural
communities, which bear the main burden of care for people with
HIV, and many HIV infected people return from the cities to their
villages when they fall ill, the report says.
</P>
<P>
Rural families provide most of the care For AIDS patients, the
households mostly bear the costs for food, medicine and funeral
expenses, and agricultural development policies rarely take this
fact into consideration, the report says.
</P>
<P>
"Rural HIV often remains silent and invisible," according to
the report, because of poor health infrastructure, restricted
access to health facilities and inadequate surveillance.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, HIV in rural population often remains "an
unknown entity for policy-makers and development planners," says
the report.
</P>
<P>
Where people are exposed to poverty, food insecurity, gender
inequality, migration, war and civil conflict, their vulnerability
to HIV increases, and in rural areas of most developing countries,
the spread of HIV is accelerated by migration, trade, the movement
of refugees and strengthened rural-urban linkages, FAO and UNAIDS
said.
</P>
<P>
The report mentions two types of rural areas particularly
vulnerable to HIV: those along truck routes and those that are
sources of migrant labor to urban areas.
</P>
<P>
According to UNAIDS, an estimated 33.6 million people were
living with HIV/AIDS at the end of 1999, of which over 90 percent
were in developing countries. Africa, which accounts for only one
tenth of the world's population, bears the brunt of the epidemic
with more than 80 percent of all deaths to date. In Asia, HIV
seropositivity rates are still comparatively low but the spread of
the pandemic is rapid. Almost 6 million people are believed to be
infected with HIV. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
