<HEADLINE> African Leaders Agree to Promote Peace, Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- African leaders Thursday
agreed that peace and economic integration are essential to launch
the continent into the global market successfully and to make the
African economic booming a reality.
</P>
<P>
"There is an urgent need to review the question of conflict on
the continent," South African President Thabo Mbeki said at the
World Economic Forum's (WEF's) 10th annual southern African
economic summit meeting held in South Africa's port city of
Durban.
</P>
<P>
The summit was organized by the WEF and the Southern African
Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said African leaders must look for ways to assist each
other in maintaining peace and stability to show the international
community that Africa is not a hopeless continent.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that African leaders should do more to discourage
conflict on the continent and ensure economic development.
</P>
<P>
African leaders, especially those in southern Africa, must
speed up the integration of their economies, he added.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Southern African Free Trade Agreement must be
concluded and enforced before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican President and Chairman of the SADC Joachim Chissano
agreed with Mbeki, saying Africans have to begin to live, instead
of just surviving.
</P>
<P>
SADC's Executive Secretary Prega Ramsamy stressed the need for
Africa to move forward into the mainstream of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
"Already steps have been taken to improve macro-economic
fundamentals of the individual countries and of the region in
which we live. But, more needs to be done," Ramsamy said. 
</P>
