<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Nigeria Get Most of Foreign Direct Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Nigeria
were getting the lion's share of the 2.1 billion U.S. dollars in
foreign direct investment (FDI) that was flowing into Africa, it
was disclosed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Much of the region's investment activity was split "westwards
where there is a heavy concentration of oil and gas" and that the
bulk of Africa' s FDI was centered around these resources, Anthony
Hawkins, head of the MBA program at the University of Zimbabwe,
said at the World Economic Forum's Southern African Development
Summit in Durban.
</P>
<P>
Paul Laudicina, vice president and managing director of U.S.
firm A.T. Kearney, said global FDI had increased four-fold during
the 1990s to a staggering sum of 850 billion dollars and that the
share that had been apportioned to the emerging markets had
averaged around 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
There had also been a steady decline in FDI in emerging markets
over the past two years, he added.
</P>
<P>
Laudicina said investors were less tolerant of risk in emerging
markets than in developed countries, adding that Africa was
perceived as the riskiest region by investors.
</P>
<P>
Hawkins said he saw investor confidence in Africa waning
because of the high costs of labor as well as geopolitical and
macro-economic instability in the region.
</P>
<P>
But interestingly, those that had invested in Africa had met
higher profitability targets than those who had invested in
Southeast Asia, according to Laudicina.
</P>
<P>
Informed investors did not regard the Southern African
Development Community as an important driver of investment but
rather as a "dream not a reality", he said.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's Minister of Finance and Development Planning Kelebone
Maope told the summit that the region did not have the necessary
infrastructure skills and human capital to address the skills
shortage that were so vital for FDI.
</P>
<P>
He urged more educational assistance and funding for the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
