<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Shas Party Decides to Remain in Ruling Coalition EDS-2nd lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Israel's ultra-Orthodox Shas
party withdrew its resignation from Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
coalition government on Thursday and said it would stay in the
government.
</P>
<P>
"The Council of Torah Sages has ordered Shas to withdraw its
resignation letters," Council secretary Rafael Pinhasi told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Council is the supreme decision-making body of Shas, which
has 17 seats in the 120-member Knesset (parliament), and thus is
the biggest coalition partner of Barak's One Israel party.
</P>
<P>
In protest against the government's failure to meet Shas'
demands for more school funding and control as well as the
legalization of its pirate radio stations, the Council last week
instructed the Shas ministers to resign.
</P>
<P>
This move plunged the 11-month-old Barak government into an "
unprecedented crisis." Barak started intensive negotiations in
efforts to prevent Shas from quitting the coalition, as he is in
dire need of Shas' support for any peace deal he may reach with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The crisis deteriorated Tuesday when the Shas ministers
submitted their letters of resignation, leaving Barak only 48 hours
of maneuvering in order to save the floundering coalition from
collapse.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing Meretz party, Shas' arch-rival, Wednesday evening
made a concession to leave the coalition, paving the way for Shas
ministers to rescind their resignation decision.
</P>
<P>
Meretz, a staunch supporter of the peace process, has vowed to
continue backing Barak in the Knesset and said they made the
sacrifice so as to bolster the government's peace efforts with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Shas' decision to stay raised the expectations that the
religious party could back Barak in his future efforts to seal a
deal with the Palestinians in return for the satisfaction of their
demands.
</P>
<P>
However, Shas political leaders so far have refrained from
pledging unreserved support for Barak in the peace process. They
say that their support for any and all peace deals is not assured.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have now entered a critical
stage with a September target date for a peace treaty looming. The
two sides have been trying to work out a framework deal to guide
the settlement of the thorniest final-status issues that include
the fate of Jerusalem, the future of settlements, borders, water
resources and refugees.
</P>
<P>
They also have to solve the interim issues, which include the
final redeployment of Israeli forces in the West Bank and the
release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Feeling a strong sense of urgency as time is running out, Barak
who used to be reluctant to attend a three-way summit with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton,
is now calling for an early meeting to help bridge the wide gaps
between the Israeli and Palestinian positions.
</P>
<P>
He is also ready to make "painful concessions" in order to
clinch a deal with the Palestinians. So far, no substantial
progress has been achieved in the interim negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Barak has sought to delay the third redeployment in the West
Bank and make it part of the framework agreement. Arafat, however,
insists on settling the interim issues first.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, after being assured by the Americans that
Israel would implement the interim accords, have also agreed to a
two-week postponement for the final Israeli redeployment in the
West Bank originally due Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is scheduled to
return to the region next week in a bid to narrow gaps and set the
stage for a possible last-ditch Barak-Arafat-Clinton three-way
summit.
</P>
<P>
Now that the government crisis is now over, it is far from
certain that Shas would live up to Barak's hope to support his
future peace deals with the Palestinians and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Barak told members of his One Israel Party on Thursday that the
emerging government, with Shas in his coalition, is the most
comfortable for advancing government policy.
</P>
<P>
Barak said the Meretz faction of the Knesset, even if not a
coalition member, is a natural partner of the government and can be
expected to support its policy.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said having Shas as a coalition partner and
Meretz's support from the outside represented the best possible
deal for his government.
</P>
<P>
Meretz party leader, and former Education Minister Yossi Sarid
Thursday said that now Shas must act appropriately as a member of
the government. He also said he expects to see Shas vote next week
in favor of transferring control of the Arab village Abu Dis
outside Jerusalem to full Palestinian control, and against a bill
to dissolve the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Whether and how long Barak's new coalition can stand the harder
tests ahead remains to be seen. As Israeli-Palestinian peace talks
move ahead, tough decisions will have to be made, which may cause
new rifts in the already shaky coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
