<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes over 60 Tons of Narcotics in 3 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRNA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran seized over 60 tons of
various narcotics in the first three months of the current Iranian
calendar year which started on March 20, a commander of the
security
forces announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Sari, the northern Mazadaran province, Brigadier
General Mohsen Ansari said the amount is 13 tons higher compared
with the same period of the last Iranian calendar year.
</P>
<P>
He said 80 percent of the drugs were seized in the eastern
provinces, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ansari said Iran has stepped up its security deployment in
the eastern and central provinces of Kerman, Sistan-Baluchestan and
Khorasan and special police dogs will be deployed in 10 cities
across the country to patrol some public places against drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Some 5,000 tons of narcotics are produced in Afghanistan
annually and because of the proximity, some of the drug cache finds
its way to Iran, the commander said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that due to the drought in Afghanistan, the
migration of Afghans to Iran is on a rise and some Afghan
immigrants carry drugs in their bags.
</P>
<P>
Iran is a main transit route for drugs smuggled from neighboring
Pakistan and Afghanistan, the world's largest opium producer, to
Europe and oil-rich Gulf Arab states.
</P>
<P>
It started strict anti-drug campaigns in 1989 after the Iranian
Majlis (parliament) passed an anti-drug law authorizing capital
punishment for drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian official said last month that over 262 tons of
various narcotics were seized in the country in the past Iranian
year that ended on March 19.
</P>
<P>
A total of 185 Iranian anti-drug forces were killed in the year
in clashes with drug traffickers, bringing the total number since
the 1979 Islamic revolution to 3,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
