<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export Posts 7 Percent Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's export earnings rose to
4.59 billion U.S. dollars in the first 10 months of the current
fiscal year (1999-2000), posting a seven percent rise, according
to an official handout released at a review meeting of the Export
Promotion Bureau (EPB) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Abdul Jalil said at the meeting that leather,
other primary commodities, raw jute, knitwear, frozen food and
petroleum products exceeded the export targets during the July-
April period of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
In the current fiscal year, some 155 private and eight state-
owned enterprises took part in 23 international fairs as part of
the country's market expansion program, according to the meeting
sources.
</P>
<P>
The commerce minister asked the EPB to set up display centers
in Bangladesh missions abroad so that foreign buyers could easily
have a first-hand idea about Bangladeshi products.
</P>
<P>
Steps to open websites in potential markets worldwide will be
taken to boost export, he said, adding that Bangladesh missions
abroad would be used in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Jalil Urged the private sector to take a lead in the market
expansion program, saying "boosting the export should be the
priority while taking part in international trade fairs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
