<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zimbabwe's Ruling, Opposition Parties To Rival In Elections (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhu Shixiang
</P>
<P>
HARARE, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabweans will go to the polls on
Saturday and Sunday to choose their fifth parliament, which is
undoubtedly the most eye-catching election in this southern
African nation.
</P>
<P>
Unlike previous elections, President Robert Mugabe's ruling
Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) this
year faces stiff competition from the labor backed Movement for
Democratic Change (MDC) led by Morgan Tsvangirai, who is former
General-Secretary of the Congress of the Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
In this year's election, at least 550 candidates from 15
political parties and 92 independent candidates will fight it out
in the 120 contested constituencies. Under the constitution,
Mugabe chooses 30 non- constituency members of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Only Zanu-pf and MDC have fielded candidates in every
constituency for the election in which one of the two would emerge
the victor.
</P>
<P>
The election has drawn much attention from the international
scene with many foreign organizations willing to come and observe
it.
</P>
<P>
Zanu-pf Deputy Secretary for Publicity and Information Chen
Chimutengwende, who is also Information Minister of the
government, said the MDC and its allies are only bent on removing
Zanu-pf from power rather than dealing with the country's social
and economic problems.
</P>
<P>
President Mugabe, who is also Zanu-pf's first Secretary, said
that his party would not be fighting MDC in the election, but
would be squaring against the British.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said, "Britain is sponsoring the MDC." "The MDC has no
history. It is unknown to the people and has no track record. The
people of Zimbabwe who have seen a revolution unfolding cannot
vote for these insignificant nobodies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zanu-pf which has been in power for 20 years is seeking yet
another mandate to make up for its shortcomings especially on the
land issue.
</P>
<P>
The party also pursues an indigenization policy so that more
blacks would own factories, mines and other businesses.
</P>
<P>
According to its election manifesto launched by Mugabe in May,
Zanu-pf's theme is that "Land is the economy and economy is the
land".
</P>
<P>
In order to get more support from people in the rural areas,
the Mugabe administration issued a preliminary notice early this
month to compulsorily acquire 804 white farms for resettlement.
</P>
<P>
The government requires 5 million hectares of land to resettle
 thousands of its landless people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zimbabwe's Ruling, Opposition Parties to Rival In Elections (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The MDC, which was formed nine months ago, said Zanu-pf's bad
rule had resulted in widespread unemployment. It will create more
jobs should it win the election.
</P>
<P>
The Zanu-pf has been the ruling party since independence from
Britain in 1980. It has made great achievements in the fields of
health, education and social welfare for the majority of poor
Zimbabweans over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
But these gains have since been affected by economic reforms
introduced in the early 1990s under the encouragement of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF). This led to steep rise in the
cost of living which has left many people suffering.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Zanu-pf is facing serious economic difficulties
because the World Bank and the IMF refuse to offer aid to it. To
grave the situation, all donor countries followed suit.
</P>
<P>
In the past four parliamentary elections, Zanu-pf got most of
the support from people in the rural areas. It has expressed the
hope to draw support from the same group of people in the
elections at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
But its popularity in cities and towns has declined because of
the country's poor economic situation. The MDC is expected to take
advantage of this to gain more votes in the cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
Out of a population of 12.5 million people, 5.1 million are
registered, among which about 70 percent live in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The Zanu-pf began armed struggle in the 1970s, which finally
led the country to independence. It initiated a massive
construction program after independence, which saw many hospitals,
schools and dams built.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts here predict that the Zanu-pf will win the
election while the MDC will become the largest opposition party in
the new Parliament.
</P>
<P>
They added that the new Parliament would have to make radical
decisions to solve problems facing the country.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the likely change to its composition, the new
Parliament is expected to deal first with the controversial land
issue. It also needs to see to boosting the country's economic
development, fighting corruption and political violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
