<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO not Ready for New Round of Trade Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Director-General of the World
Trade Organization (WTO) Mike Moore Thursday dampened hopes for an
early new round of multilateral trade negotiations, saying member
countries still have too many differences to settle.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the World Economic Forum's 10th annual southern
African economic summit meeting, Moore hinted that ministerial
talks in Seattle, the United States, last December failed to
produce the consensus on an agenda for further negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"The truth of the matter is we failed in Seattle not because of
protests, we failed because the trans-Atlantic differences were
too great and the north-south differences were too great," Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been some movement (since then) but not enough for
me to say with confidence in the short term that we can get going
rapidly," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
