<HEADLINE> Five Ugandan Battalions to Leave Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has decided
to withdraw five battalions of the Uganda People's Defence Forces
(UPDR) from the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) back to
Uganda, the President's Office said in a press release Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made following the pull-out of UPDF units from
 Kisangani and areas around the city as part of the U.N.
supervised demilitarization plan for that zone, as well as
adjustments of their dispositions in other parts of the Congo,
said the release.
</P>
<P>
As of Wednesday, the rear elements of the forces pulling out of
 Kisangani were at Lindi Bridge, about 100 kilometers north to
Kisangani, the third largest city of the DRC, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal is being supervised by the U.N. Observer team in
the Congo, said the release, adding that other forces still
remain in other parts of the DRC in accordance with the Lusaka
cease-fire agreement signed last July.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops, based in Kisangani where they back
rival rebel factions fighting against the DRC President Laurent
Kabila, clashed two weeks ago, leaving over 200 civilians dead and
more than 1,000 others wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
