<HEADLINE> WHO Offers $8 Million to Curb Polio in Horn of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) has earmarked 8 million U.S. dollars to curb polio and
related diseases in the Horn of Africa, Ethiopian News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The allocation of the money is aimed at eradicating polio and
related diseases in the border areas of Ethiopia, Sudan,
Djibouti, Kenya and Somalia, WHO bureau program head for Ethiopia
Mulugeta Lebru was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The fund will also be used to fight malaria epidemic and
meningitis and other contagious diseases in the stated border
areas, Mulugeta said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has vowed to eradicate polio by the year 2000. There
were 270 polio victims under the age of 15 across the country at
the beginning of this year, according to the Ethiopian Health
Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
