<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy, Greek FM Discuss Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's
special envoy Alvaro de Soto on Thursday met here with Greek
Foreign Minister George Papandreou to discuss the development of
the peace talks on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place just ahead of the resumption of the
third round of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot communities on the divided island of Cyprus,
which was scheduled for July 5 in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Describing the meeting as "crucial and interesting," de Soto,
who arrived in Athens after his tour to Cyprus and Turkey, said he
was looking forward to the resumption of talks on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said Annan hoped that Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
and Cypriot President Clerides would hold talks.
</P>
<P>
He also said the U.N. is trying to find a "spherical and
comprehensive solution" to the Cyprus issue, adding that Greece
should play an important role in Cyprus' reunification efforts.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou said that this was a crucial and sensitive period
for the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-brokered talks between the two sides on the
island had been held previously in New York and Geneva
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Greece, along with the Greek Cypriots and the international
community, supports the reunification of Cyprus in a federation
formula, while Turkey and the Turkish Cypriots demand that a
confederation formed by two sovereign states be set up on the
Mediterranean island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
