<HEADLINE> European Interior Ministers Meet on Police Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Interior Ministers of the member
states of the Council of Europe (CE) Thursday held their second
meeting here, discussing police efficiency in cross-border
cooperation and crackdown on international crime.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session, Romanian Interior Minister Constantin
Dudu Ionescu stressed the importance of strengthening the
protection of citizens' rights and fighting new international
threats to security.
</P>
<P>
Romanian President Emil Constantinescu said his country will
take measures to fight corruption, organized crime, illegal
migration and drug trafficking, and to seek more effective police
cooperation within the legislative framework of the CE.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the first of which was held in Strasbourg, France,
in 1998, is aimed at providing a forum on police activity,
security and protection of the citizens' rights from a pan-
European viewpoint and assessing the CE's involvement in this
process.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting was also attended by representatives of the
European Commission, the presidency of the European Union, the
Interpol and the European Commission on the Black Sea economic
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
