<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Fall 1.76 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The market turnover totaled a hefty 11.8 billion HK dollars (1.
4 billion U.S.dollars), 3.1 billion HK dollars more than the
previous trading day's 8.7 billion HK dollars, with China Unicom
accounting for 3.5 billion HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 4.92 billion U.S. dollar offering of China Unicom was the
biggest IPO ever in Asia outside Japan. It got off to a good start,
tracking a 10 percent gain on its New York debut overnight, and
hit a high of 17.30 HK dollars in midmorning, from an issue price
of 15.58 HK dollars and fell back slightly to end at 16.80 HK
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index remained moderate with a
rise of 0.30 percent to 448.92 points while the Hang Seng China-
Affiliated Corp Index went down 1.77 percent to 1,249.78 points.
</P>
<P>
All the major HSI sectors remained lower with Finance,
Utilities, Properties, and Commerce and Industry down 2.07 percent,
2.19 percent, 1.48 percent and 1.64 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Property and banking stocks were a prime target of profit
takers, traders said. Looking ahead, many market watchers expect
the market to find support at 15,800 and trade between that level
and 16,200 ahead of Tuesday's Fed meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng IT Index dropped 2.06 percent and the Hang Seng
IT Portfolio Index lost 1.81 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks fell 223.85 points, or 1.38 percent, to close
Thursday's morning session at 16,014.29. The benchmark Hang Seng
Index was down 10.67 points, or 0.07 percent, to open at 16,227.47
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
