<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Qian Qichen Meets Albright (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua)-- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
met here today with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Qian said since the heads of state of China and the United
States met for the first time in Seattle eight years ago,
generally speaking Sino-U.S. relations have experienced an overall
forward momentum, despite some twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
Qian attributed the development to the concerted efforts of the
presidents, governments and peoples of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The recent telephone conversation between President Jiang Zemin
and President Bill Clinton is of notable significance for the
healthy and stable development of Sino-U.S. ties, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
He said the current China visit by the secretary of state
herself is part of the high-level contracts between the two
countries, and he believed the visit will help enhance mutual
understanding and the further development of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Albright stressed that President Clinton and the U.S.
government attach great importance to developing U.S.-China
relations. The decision made by the two presidents that the two
countries will be committed to establishing a constructive
strategic partnership has indicated the correct direction for the
development of the bilateral relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
