<HEADLINE> Israeli Warplanes Violate Lebanese Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli warplanes violated
Lebanese skies by flying over Beirut Thursday noon, the first
provocation after the withdrawal of the Israeli occupation forces
from south Lebanon on May 24, local radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Two planes broke the sound barrier over Beirut's downtown,
witnesses were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The jets left white trails in the sky and flew away towards
north, they added.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time of Israeli violation to Lebanese skies
since
Israel promised to respect Lebanese sovereignty and ended the 22-
year occupation of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
There is no comment about the matter from the Lebanese
government so far.
</P>
<P>
Just four days ago, U.N. Security Council accepted the
conclusion
made by Secretary General Kofi Annan that Israel had fully
implemented
concerned U.N. resolutions which call for Israeli pullout from
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan has won pledge from Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to end encroachments on the Lebanese border, local newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
However, Lebanon has been complaining to the U.N. about the
Israel's violations along Lebanese-Israeli border and rejected the
Security Council's verification of Israel's full withdrawal from
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
