<HEADLINE> URGENT Israel's Shas Party Decides to Remain in Ruling Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Israel's ultra-Orthodox Shas
party decided on Thursday to remain in the ruling coalition,
shortly
before the deadline of its ministers' resignation to take effect.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced after Shas party leaders met the
party spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef. Shas leader Eli Yishai
earlier said if his party returns to the government, it will be a
full partner in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
A senior Shas official told Israel Radio that Shas, the
largest ruling partner of the One Israel alliance, achieved its
aims, and will recommend to Ovadia Yosef that Shas not quit the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Shas ministers tendered letters of resignation to Prime
Minister Ehud Barak on Tuesday, leaving the ruling One Israel only
48 hours to persuade Shas not to bolt the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Three ministers of the left-wing Meretz party, Shas' arch
rival in the ruling coalition, Wednesday night submitted letters of
resignation to the prime minister, a move considered pivotal to
clearing the obstacle for Shas to rescind their resignation
decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
