<HEADLINE> Israel's Shas Party Decides to Remain in Ruling Coalition 1st lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Shortly before the deadline of
its ministers' resignation to take effect, Israel's ultra-Orthodox
Shas party decided on Thursday to remain in the ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after Shas party leaders met the party's
spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef.
</P>
<P>
A senior Shas official told Israel Radio earlier that Shas, the
largest ruling partner of the One Israel alliance, achieved its
aims, and will recommend to Ovadia Yosef that Shas not quit the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
Shas ministers tendered letters of resignation to Prime Minister
Ehud Barak on Tuesday, leaving the ruling One Israel only 48 hours
to persuade Shas not to bolt the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Three ministers of the left-wing Meretz party, Shas' arch rival
in the ruling coalition, Wednesday night submitted letters of
resignation to the prime minister, a move considered pivotal to
clearing the obstacle for Shas to rescind their resignation
decision. During a meeting with members of his One Israel Party
on Thursday, Barak said the emerging government, with Shas in his
coalition, is the most comfortable for advancing government
policies.
</P>
<P>
Barak said the Meretz faction of the Knesset, even if not a
coalition member, is a natural partner with the government and can
be expected to support the government polices.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said having Shas as a coalition partner and
Meretz's support from the outside represents the best possible deal
for his government.
</P>
<P>
Meretz minsters have pledged their continued support for the
government even though they have left the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Meretz party leader and former education minister Yossi Sarid
Thursday said he had invested too much in efforts to resolve the
coalition crisis and is no longer interested in going from "
surrender to surrender, from blackmail to blackmail."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Tel Aviv, Sarid said now Shas
must act appropriately as a member of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
He also said he expects to see Shas vote next week in favor of
transferring control of the Arab Village of Abu Dis outside
Jerusalem to the Palestinian Authority, and against a bill to
dissolve the Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
