<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Eyes to Resume Talks with Abu Sayyaf Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Thursday that its chief negotiator, Secretary Robert Aventajado
expects to meet with the Abu Sayyaf anew in the next few days to
work out the safe release of 21 hostages in Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
According to Press Secretary and Presidential Spokesman Ricardo
Puno, Aventajado relayed this assessment after studying Abu Sayyaf
's demands, including the creation of an Islamic state in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"He has not given a specific time when it is possible for him to
go there (Sulu) in the very near future. He can safely say in the
next few days he can move there already," Puno told reporters in
the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
Puno also expressed optimism that humanitarian missions would
be able to deliver food, medicine and other forms of assistance to
the hostages as well in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, he noted, has shown some "favorable" action to
allow the medical missions to resume.
</P>
<P>
He also said a French psychiatrist will be allowed to accompany
a team in the next medical mission to tend to the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora, for his part, said the
government will convince the Abu Sayyaf to accept a package of
social development initiatives instead of ransom in exchange for
the release of 21 mostly foreign hostages.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said this approach conforms both with the government's
no-ransom policy, and with its commitment to developing Mindanao
into a land of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The 21 hostages, including two Filipinos and nationals from
Malaysia, Finland, South Africa, France, Germany and Lebanon, were
kidnapped from Sipadan Island in Malaysia on April 23 and later
taken to Jolo Island in Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the Abu Sayyaf had reunited their 10
Caucasian and 11 Asian captives, who had earlier been separated
into two groups.
</P>
<P>
Government negotiators led by Aventajado, chairman of the
presidential flagship projects committee, held talks with the Abu
Sayyaf on May 27 but failed to secure the release of the hostages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
