<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Builds Major Vocational Training Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka on Thursday laid the
foundation stone for a major vocational training complex as a part
of a massive skills development project.
</P>
<P>
"The National Technical Education and Vocational Training
Secretariat ... could be considered as the formal beginning of the
nation's massive human resources development program," said Sri
Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga in a message to mark the
event.
</P>
<P>
The complex will house a modern auditorium, a library and a
learning resources development center and the offices of many
other affiliated organizations.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Vocational Training and Rural Industries Amarasiri
Dodangoda said the new complex will enable to achieve objectives
such as improvement of the quality of vocational training courses,
introduction of competency-based training and establishing close
relationship between vocational training institutions and
industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement, "human resources development is the
sole contrivance to surmount the unemployment problem in Sri Lanka.
"
</P>
<P>
Consequently, Dodangoda's ministry has initiated a massive
Skills Development Project for a period of six years from 2000
onwards with the assistance of the Asian Development Bank with co-
financing of Nordic Development Fund and the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
The project, to cost some 38.5 million U.S. dollars, is
expected to improve the quality and relevance of skills training
programs to build a higher quality workforce and address the
issues of skills mismatch and unemployment among rural and urban
youth.
</P>
<P>
Some 100,000 youth will be directly benefited from the project
through 200 vocational training centers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
