<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. House Wednesday emphatically rejected a move to end
U.S. participation in the World Trade Organization (WTO) but sent
a message that improvements are needed in the way the body governs
world trade. In a 363 to 56 vote, lawmakers defeated a motion that
would have withdrawn Congress's approval from the accord
establishing the WTO.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Senate endorsed an aid package of nearly 1 billion
U.S. dollars Wednesday night to help Colombia equip and train
security forces to combat drug traffickers in a country where the
narcotics trade and guerrilla insurgency support each other.
</P>
<P>
-- President Laurent Kabila of the Democratic Republic of the
Congo said Wednesday that he was shutting down an effort by the
Organization of African Unity to open a political discourse among
warring factions in his country and banning the group's mediator
because he had openly criticized the government.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. conservative House Republicans took a shot at President
Bill Clinton's landmark gun-safety deal with Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp.
and missed, failing to prevent the Federal government from
implementing the pact.
</P>
<P>
-- The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries Wednesday
agreed to raise its output by 708,000 barrels a day, a little more
than expected, but not enough to bring down oil or gasoline prices
by much. 
</P>
