<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Appoints New Army Commanders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader and
Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces Ayatollah Ali Khamenei on
Thursday appointed Mustafa Torabipur as Deputy Commander of the
Army to replace Naser Arasteh.
</P>
<P>
Torabipur, former chief of joint staff of the army, was
appointed on the proposal of the newly-appointed Commander of the
Army Mohammad Salimi, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Khamenei also appointed former Deputy Chief of Staff
of the Army Shahram Rostami to replace Torabipur. However, the
report did not give the reason for the changes in the army.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei on May 21 appointed Brigadier General Mohammad Salimi
as Commander of the Army to replace Ali Shahbazi, who resigned from
the post for unknown reasons.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei made the changes amid ongoing power struggle between
the conservatives, who dominate most of sensitive organs, and the
reformists, who recently took over the parliament from the
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Iran's armed forces under Khamenei's command include three major
parts, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC), the Army and
the Security Forces (police).
</P>
<P>
The IRGC and the Army have their separate air, ground and naval
forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Asks Annan to Follow up Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on
Thursday asked visiting United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan
to continue his efforts to push forward the peace process on all
tracks.
</P>
<P>
The request was made at a joint press conference held after
their meeting in the West Bank city of Ramallah Thursday afternoon,
during which Arafat stressed the importance of enforcing the U.N.
resolutions regarding the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat discussed with Annan, who arrived in Ramallah Thursday
morning from Tel Aviv, the latest developments in the peace process
and means of boosting the process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat thanked Annan for supporting the Palestinian cause and
his efforts to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In response to a query as to the possibility of holding a
tripartite Palestine-Israel-United States summit, Arafat said what
is important is not the holding of such summits but the faithful
implementation of all signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Annan pledged to do his best to enforce all the U.
N. resolutions, particularly Resolutions 242 and 338, urging Israel
to pull out of the Arab territories it occupied during the 1967
Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. also seeks to work for progress on all tracks, said
Annan, pointing out that he supports the current U.S. mediation
over the Arab-Israeli conflict and that he makes sustained contacts
with Washington in this respect.
</P>
<P>
Before his stay in Ramallah, Annan had held talks with Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak on the Israeli-Lebanese border dispute.
</P>
<P>
Annan was expected to arrive in Damascus Thursday afternoon to
meet Syrian leaders for consultations over the peace process with
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
