<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Dip on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) shed 0.72 points to
close at 2,029.62 points in light trading.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 299.44 million units
valued at 645.13 million Singapore dollars (about 371.79 million U.
S. dollars). Declining issues edged out advancers by 157 to 117
with 271 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
TT Int was the most active stock with a turnover of 51.22
million units. ST Assemb was the second most heavily traded stock
with 36.83 million shares done. It was followed by IPC which had
14.56 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
OCBC headed the ascent of the day gaining 70 cents to close at
11.70 Singapore dollars. SPH 100 climbed up 60 cents to finish at
28.00 Singapore dollars. SPH edged up 40 cents to end at 27.60
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
ST Assemb was the biggest loser of the day incurring a loss of
115 cents to close at 4.70 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Venture sank 60 cents to finish at 17.60 Singapore dollars.
DataCrft shed 35 cents to end at 8.60 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market opened higher led by the finance
and property sector but the spurt did not last long and began to
reveres its direction in a short while.
</P>
<P>
They said that shares maintained an upward trend at most times
in the morning session and climbed to the high of 2,038.76 points
in the afternoon before a weaker close.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that leading the gainers of the day was OCBC
Bank which rose slightly over six percent after the Monetary
Authority of Singapore gave directives to banks requiring them to
implementation mandated separation of financial and non-financial
activities within three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
