<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Ex-Premier Faces Treason Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A petition was filed on Thursday
in a court in Pakistan, seeking registration of treason case
against ousted prime minister Nawaz Sharif for "leaking state
secrets" to the public.
</P>
<P>
Arif Noor, a citizen of Lahore, provincial capital of Punjab
where Sharif rose to power, prayed in his petition handed to the
Lahore High Court that a treason case be constituted against the
former prime minister, sources from Lahore told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with legal procedures, Lahore High Court has
issued notice to the Attorney General of Pakistan to appear before
the court on June 30 to explain whether treason charges should be
framed against Sharif, who had already been awarded life
imprisonment in a hijacking case and is being tried in a
corruption case.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, in his June 13 statement, accused the army chief and
the country's military ruler General Pervez Musharraf of
initiating the conflict with India in the Kargil region of Kashmir
last year.
</P>
<P>
India says Pakistan had sent intruders to Kargil while Pakistan
officially denied planing the May-June conflict with India, saying
it extended only diplomatic and political support to the insurgent
Kashmiris.
</P>
<P>
Sharif demanded formation of a high level commission to
investigate the conflict. The then prime minister claimed that he
was kept in dark by the military leadership about the Kargil
operation, saying he has irrefutable evidence to substantiate his
claim.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 Indian and Pakistani troops were killed during
the month-long battle in the Kargil region.
</P>
<P>
General Pervez Musharraf snubbed Sharif by questioning why
Sharif did not form a commission when he was the prime minister to
make the investigation. Musharraf blamed the ousted prime minister
for undermining the army.
</P>
<P>
The Kargil conflict had created differences between Sharif and
the army which many believe contributed to his dismissal in a
bloodless coup in October last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
