<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt to Install More Computers in School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Thursday that it has earmarked some 600 million pesos (15 million
U.S. dollars) for the installation of some 20,000 desktop
computers in public schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Trade Secretary Mar Roxas told a meeting that the amount will
be spent over the next 12 months as the government's counterpart
fund for the donation of brand new and used computers to public
high schools by private corporations.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly 600 million pesos will be dedicated to wiring up a
quarter of our national high schools throughout the country," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government's initiative on education was parallel to the
private-sector led program "Personal Computers for Public High
Schools."
</P>
<P>
Roxas said President Joseph Estrada formed a task force under
the trade department to coordinate with the private sector in
implementing the program.
</P>
<P>
The task force includes the Department of Education, Culture
and Sports, Department of Science and Technology and the National
Economic and Development Authority.
</P>
<P>
Roxas said under the program, 20 desktop computers for each
laboratory and one laboratory for every national high school will
be installed.
</P>
<P>
"This will immediately cut by a third the shortfall that we
have in terms of penetration and access of our children to
computers," Roxas said.
</P>
<P>
The students themselves will help sustain the program and
install more computers by paying a minimum of 100 pesos (2.5
dollars) each per semester as access fee, said Roxas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
