<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni House of Representatives (parliament) will
debate next week a loan agreement with the Arab Fund for Economic
and Social Development for financing the construction of the road
of Sihot Nashton along Yemen's eastern borders with Oman.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Yehia, a member of the parliamentary economic committee,
said the project would cost a total of 114.3 million U.S. dollars,
of which 86 million dollars are to be contributed by the Arab Fund
and the rest be shouldered by the Yemeni government.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The Moroccan government intends to invest 150 billion
dirhams (15 billion dollars) in development and economic projects
through the coming five years, said Prime Minister Abderrahmane
Youssoufi.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Moroccan parliament on June 20 on the 2000-2004
plan, he said that the tourist sector would be given a high
priority among these projects with investments hitting 750 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The International Bank for Reconstruction and
Development (IBRD) board of directors is expected on Thursday to
approve the granting of 101 million dollars to Tunisia in
contribution to financing a water project.
</P>
<P>
The project will also be financed by, in addition to the
Tunisian government, European institutions.
</P>
<P>
On June 27, the IBRD board of directors will also mull over the
granting of another loan to the educational system of Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese government has endorsed a five-year plan
to the value of 1.2 billion dollars for reconstructing south
Lebanon from which Israeli occupation forces pulled out in May.
</P>
<P>
The plan was made public following its approval by the Lebanese
cabinet during its weekly meeting held Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The five-year plan will earmark 896 million dollars on
developing infrastructure and the rest will be spent on a
comprehensive economic, social and human development plan and on
removing land mines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
