<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Motor Industry to Top ASEAN Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Malaysia's motor industry is expected to top sales in the
region with sales of new vehicles forecast to notch 348,100 units
this year and 493,000 units in 2005 against 288,547 units sold
last year, according to the EIU report made available here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report entitled "The Automotive Industries of Asia-Pacific:
prospects for ASEAN and the emerging markets to 2005" said that in
terms of models, Malaysia's three models -- Proton Wira, Perodua
Kancil and Proton Saga Iswara -- hold the top three positions in
the ASEAN car market.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's vehicle sales are estimated to grow to 273,000 units
this year and 472,000 units in 2005 against 218,372 units in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Thailand have so far experienced the most robust
recovery among the region's developing markets, EIU said.
</P>
<P>
"The ASEAN automotive sector is now bouncing back from the
devastating economic crisis of 1997/98 which crippled the region's
automotive industry," it said, adding ASEAN's average annual
vehicle sales growth to 2005 was forecast at 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
Total ASEAN vehicle sales are expected to double from 741,218
units in 1999 to about 1.47 billion in 2005, it added.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore and Vietnam besides Malaysia and Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
