<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moody's Upgrades Thailand's Sovereign Rating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Moody's Investors Service
announced Thursday that it had upgraded Thailand's sovereign
credit rating to investment grade from "junk" status, citing the
country's broad economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The influential U.S. credit rating agency said in a statement
that it had raised Thailand's country ceiling for foreign-currency
long-term bonds and notes to Baa3, the lowest investment grade,
from Ba1, or junk status, and placed a stable outlook on the new
rating.
</P>
<P>
The agency also raised the long-term debt and deposit ratings
of 12 Thai banks and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda welcomed the
announcement, saying that it would help encourage new investment
and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The action on the banks meant that the agency understood
Thailand's efforts to restructure the economy and banking sector
after the 1997 financial crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
The upgrade comes two-and-a-half years after Moody's cut
Thailand's debt to junk status. The devaluation of the Thai baht
in July 1997 triggered the Asian financial crisis and crippled
Thailand's economy and banking system.
</P>
<P>
In a series of moves in 1997, Moody's slashed Thailand's long-
term debt rating from A2 to Ba1.
</P>
<P>
Now Thailand's rating is the same as Malaysia's and one notch
below South Korea's. While Thailand's rating is still four notches
below its level at the beginning of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Moody's said that its action was prompted by Thailand's
prospects for a balance of payments performance that would support
a substantial improvement in the country's external liquidity
position and reduce vulnerability to external shocks.
</P>
<P>
The country's economy returned to growth last year after
shrinking 10.2 percent in 1998. The latest official forecast said
that the economy is expected to grow 5.5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the broadening economic recovery and
strengthening of the country's institutions had made the financial
sector more stable. And there was evidence of progress being made
in corporate debt restructuring.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, further legal and institutional reforms were
necessary to help resolve difficulties faced by Thai corporations
and to ensure the financial sector will be able to support a
sustained recovery.
</P>
<P>
Moody's said future ratings would be determined by the
authorities' ability to maintain "prudent and flexible" policies
to prevent a recurrence of the problems that triggered the economy
into crisis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On the bank upgrades, Moody's said Thailand's financial system
continued to be weak, though all institutions have embarked upon
wide ranging reforms.
</P>
<P>
Despite a sometimes volatile stock market, and fluctuating
investor confidence, it is increasingly likely that the major Thai
banks will be able to restore their capital bases over a
reasonable period, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
Moody's also praised Thai government measures taken since the
crisis, saying that they had restored funding stability.
</P>
<P>
The rating agency raised the bank financial strength ratings of
three major Thai commercial banks, which are Bangkok Bank, Thai
Farmers Bank and Siam Commercial Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
