<HEADLINE> Portugal Reiterates Political Solution to Angolan Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime
Gama has reiterated the need for a political solution to the
Angolan civil war although the European Union (EU) has expressed
"clearly" its support for the U.N. sanctions against the Angolan
rebels led by Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Gama made the remarks after receiving an Angolan parliamentary
delegation, said a report by the Portuguese Lusa News Agency
reaching here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Such a solution should be based on the 1991 and 1994 peace
accords signed respectively in Bicesse, Portugal and Lusaka,
Zambia, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said this stance came after the Monday-Tuesday EU summit in
northern Portugal, adding that it is a common position that
enhances as core element for resolution of the Angolan questions.
</P>
<P>
The position is also an appeal to all, whether members of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola or other
parties, to take a political stance on the path of peace, he said.
</P>
<P>
Angola has suffered over 25 years of civil conflicts since 1975
when the southern African country gained independence from the
Portuguese colonists.
</P>
<P>
Accusing Savimbi of failing to keep his promise during the 1992
general elections and refusing to fulfill the Lusaka Protocol, the
Angolan government has decided not to deal with Savimbi, local
analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
