<HEADLINE> Tanzania Jails 165 Burundian Refugees for Decamping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A Tanzanian court has
sentenced three to six months jail terms to 165 Burundians who
fled the refugee camps in a bid to join the rebels fighting in
Burundi, local newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The western Kigoma regional court found Wednesday the
Burundians guilty of illegal decamping from three refugee camps in
Kibondo District last month, a senior police officer was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian laws set that all the refugees should be confined to
their camps for fear of disturbing local residents.
</P>
<P>
The Kigoma Regional Police Commander, Assistant Commissioner of
Police Placid Chaka, said that all the 165 Burundian refugees
refused to go back to the refugee camps, but wanted to be
repatriated to their motherland to join a main rebel force, the
National Council for Defense of Democracy- Forces for Defense of
Democracy (CNDD-FDD).
</P>
<P>
Chaka said the Burundian refugees, all of Hutu origin, were
arrested by the police in Kibondo on May 18 when they were
travelling in two vehicles from their camps in Karago, Mtendeli
and Nduta in the Kigoma region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) has reiterated its call on Tanzanian government to allow
refugees living in camps to engage themselves in self-supporting
activities.
</P>
<P>
In her speech to commemorate Africa Refugee Day on Tuesday at
Lukole Refugee Camp in Ngara District, the UNHCR Representative in
Tanzania Marjon Kamara also called on refugees to respect the laws
of Tanzania and abide by the established requirement of refugees
status.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Ministry of Home Affairs said early this week that
the country was hosting more than 800,000 refugees from
neighboring Burundi, Rwanda and the DRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
