<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Set Up Telecenter to Serve Triangular Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique is to set up a
telecenter in the western province of Tete to facilitate
communications between the areas covered by the "Triangular
Development" project between Mozambique, Malawi and Zambia, local
media reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A project mission of business people, including a
representative of the Canadian government, visited Tete recently,
the report said, adding that Canada is among the potential sources
of finance for the project.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, the project aims to promote trade and
investment between the three member countries of the Southern
African Development Community.
</P>
<P>
"The consensus reached by the business mission was that it is
feasible to set up a telecenter in that province, taking into
account that it will be a means to facilitate communication
between business people, students, and farmers," Tete provincial
governor Virgilio Ferrao was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
It could also assist in the implementation of projects,
particularly in the areas of health and education, "which will
mean an advance in all areas of human life for the three countries
involved", he said.
</P>
<P>
Similar telecenters have already been set up elsewhere in
Mozambique, and in some regions of Malawi and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Existing Mozambican telecenters, under a pilot project run by
the computer center of the Eduardo Mondlane University, provide
users with access to e-mail and the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
