<HEADLINE> British Defense Secretary to Visit China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary Geoff
Hoon is scheduled to visit China next week as an official guest of
the Chinese government, the Ministry of Defense said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary will arrive in China next Monday, where
he will meet his Chinese counterpart, General Chi Haotian, a
defense ministry spokesman told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Hoon will also deliver a speech to the Chinese National Defense
University on North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in the
21st Century.
</P>
<P>
Together with Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, Hoon will
open a United Kingdom-China joint peacekeeping seminar in Beijing.
The aim of this seminar is to enhance Sino-UK liaison and
cooperation, and to exchange views on the challenges involved in
peacekeeping in the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
Defense cooperation with China forms an important part of
Britain's overall policy of engagement with the Chinese on a wide
range of issues, a statement issued by the defense ministry said.
</P>
<P>
As a fellow permanent member of the Security Council, Britain
want to work with China in promoting international and regional
security issues, it said.
</P>
<P>
Since the Prime Minister Tony Blair's visit to China in October
1998, Britain and China have committed themselves to strengthening
and expanding their political-military dialogue, and to a program
of senior military visits and ministerial exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Hoon will leave China on June 29, according to the program.
Hoon is scheduled to visit South Korea prior to his visit to China.
</P>
</TEXT>
