<HEADLINE> Lebanese Cabinet Agrees on Billion-Dollar Aid to South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese government approved
Wednesday a 1.2-billion-U.S. dollar reconstruction plan for south
Lebanon, recently liberated from the 22-year Israeli occupation,
Daily Star newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The five-year plan, prepared by the Council for Development and
Reconstruction, will earmark 896 million dollars on developing
infrastructure, said Post, Telephone and Telegram Minister Issam
Naaman after a weekly cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The rest will be spent on a comprehensive economic, social and
human development plan and on removing land mines, the minister
added.
</P>
<P>
Economy Minister Nasser Saidi told Lebanon Radio that the plan
will develop the roads and water, irrigation, telephone and power
systems of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the plan also provides for developing
schools and health-care centers in the south. Much of the projects
will be carried out by the private sector, under the Build-Operate-
Transfer mode, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, ministers also approved an economic
cooperation agreement with the United Arab Emirates as well as a
loan from Belgium's Fortis Bank to finance development projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
