<HEADLINE> Manila Offers Development Package for Hostages' Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Thursday that it will convince the extremist Abu Sayyaf to accept
a package of social development initiatives instead of ransom in
exchange for the release of 21 mostly foreign hostages.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said this approach conforms
both with the government's no-ransom policy, and with its
commitment to develop Mindanao into a land of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"We expect them to demand ransom in the end. But we will try to
convince them to accept social development projects instead of
ransom.We have said this long ago," Zamora said in a radio
interview.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the government's stand that any parallel
negotiation by foreign governments with the Abu Sayyaf must be
limited to humanitarian concerns, such as medical aid and food
supplies for the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the government recognizes the concern of foreign
governments to make sure that their hostaged nationals get food,
medicine and other supplies while in captivity.
</P>
<P>
The hostages include two Filipinos and nationals from Malaysia,
Finland, South Africa, France, Germany and Lebanon. They were
kidnapped from Sipadan Island in Malaysia on April 23 and later
taken to Jolo Island in Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Robert Aventajado earlier said foreign governments
whose nationals are among the hostages have reiterated support for
Manila's handling of the situation.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado, who chairs the presidential flagship projects
committee, has been tasked by President Joseph Estrada to head a
government panel negotiating for the safe release of the hostages.
</P>
</TEXT>
