<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah not to Drop Further: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Coordinating Minister
for Economy, Finance and Industry, Kwik Kian Gie said here
Thursday that the exchange rate of rupiah (national currency) will
not plunge into further lower level.
</P>
<P>
Denying of predictions that rupiah will slump to the level of 9,
000 rupiah per U.S. dollar if the detention of Central Bank
Governor,Syahril Sabirin is left unclear, Kwik said, " In a free
floating system, wherever it is, no one can say yes or no."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Attorney General Office detained Sabirin for
20 days on the charges of his involvement in the Bali Bank scandal
which made the country lost about 130 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday morning trade session, rupiah traded at 8,600 (
buying)and 8,750 (selling) for one U.S. dollar or lower than the
previous day when it traded at 8,500 (buying) and 8,650 rupiah (
selling) per U.S.dollar.
</P>
<P>
Kwik also said he was optimistic that the country's economic
recovery process will not be affected by any disturbance within
the central bank, saying that Indonesia's macroeconomy condition
is good.
</P>
<P>
"All the indicators are good," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Keep Waiting for Int'l Financial System Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The pegging of the ringgit at 3.80 to the US dollar and the
imposition of selective exchange controls on September 2, 1998, "
would stay as long as the international financial architecture is
not reformed," he told a conference here organized by the
Malaysian-Australian Business Council.
</P>
<P>
The adviser said that despite some estimates that the ringgit
was undervalued by 15 to 20 percent, the government felt that the
undervaluation was only between 6 and 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government would be concerned about undervaluation only if
there was a wide distortion of 40 to 50 percent over a long period
of time, he said.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the recent regional financial crisis to the
manipulative trading of hedge funds, saying their attacks on
regional currencies had caused loss of confidence.
</P>
<P>
He said the Malaysian economy would not have contracted by as
much as 7.5 percent in 1998 if not for the unscrupulous actvities
of the hedge funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
