<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's unemployment rate remained at 9 percent in
April, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS). For the
last three months, the unemployment rate has not changed and the
rate for the last nine months has stayed between 9 percent and 9.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A new law on state subsidies for research and
development should give companies the option of receiving less
money but not paying royalties, the Israeli Manufacturers'
Association has proposed.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Finance and Industry Ministries are in the process
of revising the existing research and development law, and the
association is preparing its own proposals in an effort to
influence the process.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Foreign investment in Israeli stocks and real
estate came to 4.31 billion U.S. dollars during the first five
months of the year -- more than double the total for all of 1999
with 2.06 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Israel statistics show that direct foreign investment
came to 1.08 billion dollars in the January-May period, compared
with 1.27 billion dollars for all of 1999. Investments in stocks,
however, came to 3.2 billion dollars -- four times the 1999 total
of 788 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's Aegean region has very important geothermal
reserves which could heat 465,000 buildings in Izmir, Turkey's
third largest city, said Chairman of the European Geothermal
Association Orhan Mertoglu.
</P>
<P>
He said that geothermal energy is four times cheaper in terms of
its initial construction in home heating compared to natural gas.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The world's second largest computer company Dell will
embark on a restructuring program to improve internet
infrastructure and the development of e-commerce in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Dell Developing Markets Director Glenn Jones said in Istanbul
Wednesday that through the post-sales education services of their
Turkish distributors, they would provide complete Internet
infrastructure solutions to all personal and institutional users
wanting to convert to e-business.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's Vestel Elektronik company plans to make its
debut on the international bond markets next week.
</P>
<P>
The company is looking to raise 150-200 million dollars and may
add a euro tranche if demand is sufficient. Vestel' offering
provide diversification from a barrage of recent sovereign debt
issues. Vestel will become the second Turkish company after
Turkcell, the country largest mobile phone operator, to establish
itself in the international bond markets.
</P>
<P>
Vestel, which manufactures televisions and personal computer
monitors, will use proceeds from the bond to refinance existing
bank debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
