<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Parliament Urges for Withdrawal of Troops From Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan parliament has passed a
resolution urging the government to withdraw the Uganda People's
Defense Forces (UPDF) from the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC), the New Vision daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Parliament urges the government to organize withdrawal of UPDF
troops from Congo in accordance with the Lusaka ceasefire
agreement," the resolution reads.
</P>
<P>
The House, presided over by Speaker Francis Ayume, also passed
a resolution requiring the government to brief it monthly about
the implementation of the Lusaka peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The resolutions were passed during a stormy session that marked
the end of debate on the petition of Parliament Member Winnie
Byanyima on recent clashes between Ugandan and Rwandan troops in
the northeast DRC city of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
The House, however, rejected a draft resolution urging the
government to utilize all established official channels including
parliament to promote a peaceful relationship with Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops, based in Kisangani where they back
rival rebel factions fighting to topple DRC President Laurent
Kabila, clashed two weeks ago, leaving more than 200 civilians
dead and over 1,000 others wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
