<HEADLINE> Water Shortage to Worsen in Kenya's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The water shortage is expected to
worsen in the Kenyan capital Nairobi as water levels at the dams
continue to drop due to poor rainfall.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Thursday quoted acting Town
Clerk Godfrey Mate as saying that water rationing, which has been
imposed in the higher districts of the city, will now be extended
to the lower districts including the city center.
</P>
<P>
Water levels at the dams have fallen to "worrying levels" since
the water rationing began in the city a week ago, Mate said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is currently threatened by a prolonged drought, the worst
in the past 20 years. About 22 million Kenyans, 80 percent of the
country's population, have been pushed to the verge of starvation.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
