<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Lambastes Private Oil Firms for Creating Fuel Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has lambasted private oil
marketing companies for creating an artificial fuel shortage in
the country, Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Energy and Water Development Deputy Minister Celestino Chibamba
was quoted by the newspaper as saying in an interview in Lusaka on
Wednesday that what appeared to be a fuel shortage in the country
had been caused by private oil marketing companies that did not
want to pay the Zambia National Oil Company (ZNOC) in advance for
the commodity.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said these oil companies who are refusing
to pay in advance were responsible for supplying fuel to service
stations.
</P>
<P>
Chibamba said ZNOC has been unable to get the commodity from the
 warehouse due to non-payment by private oil companies.
</P>
<P>
Zambia had enough stocks of fuel to last a considerably longer
period, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government would not allow a situation where dealers take
measures that adversely affected the country and the people, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Chibamba said there should be no excuse or fuel shortage as all
private companies were given permits to import their own petroleum
products.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, prices of petroleum products went up
by 33 percent three weeks ago. Sweet light crude oil had gone up
to 33 U.S. dollars per barrel form 24 dollars while petrol was now
pegged at 390 per ton from 280 dollars. Gas oil was increased to
230 dollars per ton from 200 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some filling stations in Lusaka have had no fuel for almost a
week now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
