<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Reduces Life Expectancy to 34 Years in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- HIV/AIDS has taken off no less than
15 years from the healthy life expectancy of the most affected
countries with Zambia' s life expectancy falling to less than 34
years, Zambian newspaper, The Post, reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Launching the World Health Report 2000 in Lusaka on Wednesday,
World Health Organization (WHO) representative Edward Maganu said
HIV/AIDS was a major contributor to the disability adjusted life
expectancy at birth of between 25.9 and 34.9 years in most African
countries, particularly in sub- Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
Maganu said according to WHO assessment, it did not follow that
the more a government spends on health systems, the higher its
performance.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Zambia has been ranked 182 with a
total health expenditure as a share of its Gross Domestic Product
(GDP) of between 5.3 and 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The highest spender on health according to the report was the
United States with a GDP portion of 10.5-13.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
