<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police Step up Efforts to Ensure Peaceful Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Zimbabwean policemen
have been deployed throughout the country to ensure a peaceful
parliamentary election at the weekend, with patrols increased in
areas where political violence has been rife.
</P>
<P>
A significant number of policemen would be guarding polling
stations on a 24-hour basis starting from Wednesday night until
the last ballot box is delivered to the counting station, said
police spokesman Chief Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said apart from the deployment of officers, the police have
also put in place other measures which include the revoking of
leave days and maintaining the Law and Order (Maintenance) Act
which was invoked in April following the eruption of countrywide
political violence, local media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Several special reaction units have also been deployed on
standby as back-up to the officers, he said, adding that the
police have recalled the " Crocodile" armored vehicles and bought
state-of-the-art telecommunication equipment to ensure that they
swiftly enter trouble spots, should any violence occur.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the elections will run smoothly because
we have put in place special measures which revolve around
Wednesday's massive deployment of officers to the provinces," he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman called on people to enjoy their weekend
as usual, saying that the only thing they need to remember is to
behave well and not to flout any electoral laws.
</P>
<P>
At the weekend, no gathering of more than 12 people is allowed
within 100 meters of a polling station, he said, stressing that
people should avoid sloganeering or canvassing for votes within
that distance.
</P>
<P>
Members of the public should secure their houses when going to
vote since some criminal elements are likely to take advantage of
the situation to break into homes, he said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six people have died, 185 others injured and property
worth millions of U.S. dollars destroyed in over 300
politically-motivated clashes that have occurred since February
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
