<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facilitator Office for Congo Issue Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The office of Ketumile Masire,
facilitator in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) peace
mission, has been closed, said Zambia President Frederick Chiluba
here on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Times of Zambia newspaper quoted the president as
saying in an interview at the State House that he had received
disturbing news that DRC President Laurent Kabila had shut the
office in Kinshasa over some disagreement.
</P>
<P>
He described the action as ill-timed because tremendous
progress has been made toward restoring peace in the trouble-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
"This is coming at a time when fighting in Kisangani between
Uganda and Rwanda has been brought to an end and the two parties
are ready to leave control of Kisangani for the United Nations
forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Masire's role is to facilitate dialogue, I only hope internal
dialogue can take place especially so that terms of the Lusaka
agreement can be complied with," Chiluba said. Masire is former
president of Botswana.
</P>
<P>
According to Chiluba, he would contact U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan and Kabila to try and resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
This is not the sort of setback that should prevent the
implementation of the peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that both the Joint Military Council and the U.N.
forces have made tremendous progress to pave way for the arrival
of the nearly 5,000 peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
Peace is vital to the DRC as the overall investment prospects
depended on political stability in the whole region, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
