<HEADLINE> Bird Island to Be Recovered From Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic International Trust
and Investment Company in northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region plans to invest 100 million yuan (about 12.04 million U.S.
dollars) to rebuild an island habitat for birds on the upper
reaches of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The three-year project will be carried out by turning farmland
into forests, grassland, and water areas.
</P>
<P>
The bird island, located at the Qingtong Gorge Reservoir on the
upper reaches of the Yellow River, was formed in the 1960s by sand
which had washed into the reservoir.
</P>
<P>
Every year, the 3,133.3-hectare island attracted more than 300,
000 birds in 170 varieties.
</P>
<P>
But in later years, birds were rarely seen on the island, where
large areas of forest had been cut for timber and other land had
been sewn with crops.
</P>
<P>
This year, the investment company wants to turn 1.333 hectares
of farmland into water areas, 800 hectares of farmland into
grassland, and build 40 kilometers of roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Credit System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to greatly
improve its credit system in two to three years to meet the
demands of the market economy and electronic businesses.
</P>
<P>
A credit appraisal system will be set up nationwide this year,
said Chen Jing, an official with the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
The system began on a trial basis in 300 cities last year.
Shanghai started a consumption credit evaluation system for
individuals with the final goal to realize online consultation
among banks.
</P>
<P>
Chen is confident that an improved credit evaluation system
will be set up in two to three years in China, adding that it will
promote a healthy development of the market economy and e-business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
