<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Resettle Police-rescued Abducted Women and Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Police units across China will
help resettle women and children they have rescued, a notice
issued by the Ministry of Public Security says.
</P>
<P>
"The work of resettlement can cap the achievement of the
nationwide crackdown on traffickers of women and children, which
kicked off on April 1st," the notice reads.
</P>
<P>
China began its current "hukou" system, or the permanent
residence registration system, in the late 1950s, as a way to
ensure the accurate and timely control of the country's population
information.
</P>
<P>
According to the notice, police departments will help regain
the residence rights of those rescued women and children whose
registration certificates had been revoked after their
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
The notice stipulates that police should also respect the
wishes of the newly-freed abducted women if they choose to marry
in accordance with Chinese law with their "husbands" who had
previously bought their wives illicitly, and help those women to
find new homes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
