<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Hezbullah, or Party of God, is a full-pledged regional
player, and should not be ignored in any peace settlement, visiting
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan indicated on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Annan also said that Hezbullah Secretary General Sheikh Hassan
Nasrallah had told him the organization intends no further military
action, but instead looks to establish its political structure in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint conference with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, Annan brushed off criticism that in meeting with Nasrallah
earlier this week, he had given the organization unwarranted
legitimacy, saying it is his duty to work with all involved
parties.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Barak on Wednesday accepted the resignation of three cabinet
ministers from the left-wing Meretz party, which has been long in
dispute with the ultra-Orthodox Shas party over funding for the
latter's school system.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the Meretz ministers that he regretted their decision
and appreciated the concession they had made in order to enable the
peace process to continue.
</P>
<P>
Barak did not try to persuade the Meretz ministers to reconsider
their decision. Meretz has pledged to support the government as if
it were still part of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv
</P>
<P>
-- A 41-year-old man, Reuven Sheinfeld, Wednesday shot dead his
wife, 40, and then committed suicide in their home in Haifa, a
northern coastal city of Israel.
</P>
<P>
It was the latest in a growing wave of violence rocking the
country.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the couple were found by their 16-year-old
daughter when she returned home. Police said it appeared that the
couple were in the process of getting divorced.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Barak has decided to intensify his government's dialogue with
the Jewish settlers in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Barak spoke of
the need for an "ongoing and thorough dialogue" between the sides,
following his meetings with the settler leaders during the last
year.
</P>
<P>
He instructed his ministers to travel to settlements with senior
government officials and meet with the residents there, who have
been fighting against further land transfer to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
At the security cabinet meeting on Wednesday, the ministers
called for more concessions toward the Palestinians, in an attempt
to forge an agreement. 
</P>
