<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Vows to Improve Health Services for Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Health authorities of the
Philippines assured the public Thursday that the government
continues to strive to improve health services for Filipinos,
especially the poor.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Alberto Romualdez of the Department of Health (DOH)
said the government has sought the assistance of the World Health
Organization (WHO) in reforming areas of Philippine health care
that need improvement.
</P>
<P>
"We will look at our citizens' health status. Then we'll see
what needs to be done with the system to address problems in
health care,"Romualdez said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez issued the statement in reaction to reports that the
Philippines ranked 60th in terms of health care among 191
countries surveyed by the WHO.
</P>
<P>
"We will study the factors that figured in our ranking so that
we can solve problems in areas that the WHO thinks still need
improvement," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the DOH is to launch a health sector reform
agenda Friday, in time for its 102nd anniversary. The program aims
to introduce improvements to the health care program.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez said the agenda aims to make sure poor and unemployed
Filipinos are able to avail themselves of health care service.
</P>
<P>
According to Romualdez, this includes "health passport" that
allows the bearers access to medical care from government and the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
He said the DOH has started implementing the program by giving
health insurance to its own employees, and to indigent Filipinos.
The next target of the health insurance program are self-employed
Filipinos, said Romualdez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
