<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Speaker Regrets Over Bank Governor Detention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Indonesia's House
of Representatives (DPR) Akbar Tandjung said here Thursday that
his side regretted over the detention of the country's Central
Bank Governor Syahril Sabirin and hoped there will be a fair trial
against him.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the press conference here after presiding over a
special meeting with members of Board of Director of Bank
Indonesia,Tandjung said, "After studying reasons of the detention
of Bank Indonesia's governor, I think that such reasons are not
reasonable."
</P>
<P>
The Attorney General's Office spokesman Yushar Yahya announced
a 20-day detention of Sabirin Wednesday, saying it was to
facilitate the investigation into him on the charges of the Bali
Bank scandal.
</P>
<P>
The scandal revolves around Bank Indonesia's (the central bank)
reimbursement of 904 billion rupiah (129 million U.S. dollars) in
defaulted loans to other banks. Some 546 billion rupiah (78
million U.S. dollars) of the money was then paid to PT Era Giat
Prima for helping Bali Bank recoup the money. There is suspicion
that a large portion of the money went to help the then ruling
party of Golkar to run for its presidential renomination of BJ.
Habibie.
</P>
<P>
Tanjung, who is also Golkar party's general chairman, said, "I
know him (Syahril Sabirin). He is very cooperative with
prosecutors and it is impossible for him to make evidences
disappear or running away," he said, adding that he will soon ask
President Abdurrahman Wahid and Attorney General Marzuki Darusman
about the detention of Sabirin.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin, one of several former ministers who have been
allegedly involved in the Bank Bali scandal, was named as suspect
early this month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Senior Deputy of Bank Indonesia's Governor, Anwar
Nasution said that he has taken over tasks of Sabirin as the
central bank governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
