<HEADLINE> Nokia Starts New Plant in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 22 (Xinhua) -- World-leading mobile phone maker
Nokia has begun production at its new 20-million-U.S.-dollar plant
in Dongguan of south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The new factory, with a floor space of 100,000 square meters,
is equipped with the world's most advanced mobile phone
manufacturing technology.
</P>
<P>
Nokia expects the facility to help increase the exports of its
products. Nokia hopes that this year's exports will make up 50
percent of its total production output, and its local purchases
will also account for half the total.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 Nokia started up its first mobile phone company in
Dongguan in cooperation with a local telecommunications
development firm. The joint venture, which mainly produces digital
mobile phones, turned out the world's first WAP (wireless
application protocol) mobile phone in May 1999. Last year, Nokia
exported 38 percent of its output in Dongguan, with the value of
the exports surpassing one billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company has so far invested more than one billion U.S.
dollars in China, which is the giant mobile phone maker's second
largest market worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecological Deterioration Curbed on Upper Reaches of Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- China's efforts to curb the
deteriorating natural environment on the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River, the world third largest, have paid off, satellite
remote sensing studies show.
</P>
<P>
A satellite investigation of the area shows that the soil
erosion in provinces of Yunnan and Sichuan, and Chongqing
Municipality has markedly eased.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan, Sichuan and Chongqing, which are located in the valleys
of the Jinsha River and Jialing River, and the Three Gorges
Reservoir area respectively suffer the most serious soil erosion,
or 90 percent of the total on the upper reaches of the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
The study reveals that compared with 1987, the annual amount of
eroded soil dropped by 11 percent, from the former 1.5 billion
tons to the current 1.339 billion tons. The amount of eroded soil
per square kilometer went down from 5,118.7 tons to 4,216.8 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River valley accounts for one-fifth of the country'
s total land area, one-fourth of the total arable land, one-third
of the total population and two-fifths of the total industrial and
agricultural output value.
</P>
<P>
China launched a water and soil conservation project on the
lower reaches of the Jinsha River, the middle and lower reaches of
the Jialing River and the Three Gorges Reservoir area in 1989.
Later, a project for building shelter forests also started along
the middle and upper reaches of the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
The country has so far spent 1.2 billion yuan (about 144
million U.S. dollars) on the water and soil conservation project
and harnessed some 60,000 square kilometers of eroded areas. The
vegetation coverage rate in the project zone has increased from 22
percent to 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the project zones combined, the eroded area has dropped from
65 percent to 36 percent. The total grain output has risen by more
than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the shelter forest project has helped improve
the vegetation coverage rate from 20 percent to 25 percent in the
project areas. The soil erosion in over 100 counties basically has
been controlled.
</P>
<P>
An expert from the Ministry of Water Resources warned that they
still have a long way to go to restore the environment in the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Golden Monkey Population Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Some 2,000 golden monkeys, one of
the world's most endangered species, are living in the Tibetan
Autonomous Prefecture of Diqing of Yunnan Province, southwest
China.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Qikun, a researcher from the Kunming Animals Research
Institute under the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said that the
Yunnan golden monkey population has increased rapidly in recent
years because more nature reserves have been built to protect them.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that over 500 golden monkeys were recently found in
the forests in Tacheng Township, south of Baima Snow Mountain,
where most of the creatures live.
</P>
<P>
"It is still not clear where these monkeys have come from,"
Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists confirmed that there were only 600 golden monkeys in
the Baima Snow Mountain area in the 1980s; by the early 1990s, the
figure had risen to 1,500.
</P>
<P>
The Yunnan golden monkey is called a state treasure, just like
the giant panda.
</P>
<P>
The state invests one million yuan (120,000 U.S. dollars)
annually to protect the rare species.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jinan Gets More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Jinan, capital of east China's
Shandong Province now has 865 overseas-funded enterprises,
actually using 1.25 billion US dollars of overseas money.
</P>
<P>
Jinan has introduced more than 3,000 sets of overseas advanced
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The city has so far established commercial and trade ties with
more than 60 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
This is due to an improved local investment environment,
including increased enforcement of legal systems to safeguard the
interests of overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded projects have become an increasingly important
part of the local export-oriented economy and a number of overseas-
funded enterprises are mushrooming locally, including those funded
by Matsushita, Siemens, and Suzuki.
</P>
<P>
Jinan supports overseas-funded enterprises which invest more
than five million US dollars, more than one million US dollars of
exports annually, and more than one million yuan in pre-tax
profits a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
