<HEADLINE> Fiji Coup Leader Holds Off Signing Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Prospects for an immediate end to
Fiji's hostage crisis have again been delayed and the 31 captives
are not expected to be released until at least Friday, the
Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Fiji's military commander Frank Bainimarama and Speight were
scheduled to sign an accord to establish an interim government
Thursday, thereby allowing the hostages to go free.
</P>
<P>
But Speight's group claimed the military had redrafted
provisions in the agreement since it was reached on Wednesday
night, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
Speight's group said the accord is now likely to be signed on
Friday, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would end the five-week-old political crisis
during which the hostages have been held inside parliament.
</P>
<P>
It sets a timetable for the installation of a new government
and outlines the role of the military.
</P>
<P>
The ABC quoted military spokesman Filipo Tarakinikini as saying
both sides are now looking to see the 31 hostages freed by the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
"There's optimism not only to this crisis but also to a country
as whole that we are coming to a close here and I think we should
capture the moment," he said. 
</P>
