<HEADLINE> Manila to Draw up Mindanao Rehab Plan in 60 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Secretary Jose Pardo of the Department of Finance said the
government is eyeing access to funds from the United Nations (UN)
if it can draw up an acceptable proposal for the plan.
</P>
<P>
"I think we would have access to funds from the UN because they
do have special funds for displaced groups. Therefore (we think)
in 60 days we'll have a proposal in place," Pardo said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries and institutions had earlier committed new
pledges amounting to 2.6 billion U.S. dollars for the Philippines
in a recent Consultative Group Meeting in Tagaytay city, of which
over 360 million dollars will go to Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Pardo said that the proposed funding from the UN for the
Mindanao rehabilitation plan is separate from the pledges gained
by the Philippines during the Consultative Group Meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said the foreign aid would supplement the regular relief
funds earmarked by government agencies such as the Departments of
National Defense and Social Welfare and Development for Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The National Economic and Development Authority, Pardo noted,
will call meetings within the next few weeks to put together the
proposed Mindanao rehabilitation plan.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is trying to turn Mindanao into the
country's another food basket, which was hindered by the continued
conflict in that region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
