<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Repair of Ancient City Wall Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 22 (Xinhua) -- An eight-year-project to repair the
eastern gate tower of the city wall built during the Ming Dynasty
(1368-1644) in Xi'an, northwest China's Shaanxi Province, has been
completed.
</P>
<P>
The 48,000-U.S. dollar project recovered the original styles
and features of the ancient city wall when it was built more than
600 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an, the capital of 12 dynasties in the Chinese history, has
3,000 historical sites. The 14-km-long ancient city wall is now
the best preserved city wall in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Changle Gate Tower, the eastern gate tower of the ancient
city wall, has been damaged many times, especially during times of
war.
</P>
<P>
The repair project started in 1992 when the gate tower tilted
more than 10 degrees, part of the roofing collapsed and some of
the roof beams were broken.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0250 </DOCNO>
