<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former USOC Drug Chief Says 50 Percent of U.S. Drug Offenders Unpunished </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The former drug chief of the U.
S. Olympic Committee (USOC) has claimed that half of all American
athletes who tested positive for banned substances went unpunished
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Wade Exum, who resigned as the USOC's director of drug control
administration on June 5 this year, plans to pursue the accusation
in a federal lawsuit expected to be filed next month. He had
worked for the USOC for the past nine years.
</P>
<P>
USOC denied the claim in Denver on Wednesday. "We find it
incredible that the individual charged with the direction and the
success of our own drug program now is criticizing it and
challenging its effectiveness," USOC spokesman Mike Moran said.
</P>
<P>
"He's going to have to back up those allegations with facts,
and we expect to be able to effectively deal with those
allegations," Moran added.
</P>
<P>
Exum said he had become a "racial token" subjected to a hostile
and intolerable working environment. In the resignation letter he
also said the USOC encouraged the doping of athletes without
regard to their health.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday Exum and his lawyers issued a news release, saying:
"In recent years, absolutely no sanction has been imposed on
approximately 50 percent of all the American athletes who have
tested positive for prohibited substances."
</P>
<P>
Exum's lawsuit also is expected to include claims he was asked
to take part in a project that involved testing prohibited
substances on humans "using a protocol that amounted to racial
profiling."
</P>
<P>
Exum also complained his authority was undermined by having to
work under the supervision of Jim Page, currently the USOC's
managing director of sport development. Page was banned from the
U.S. Skiing Association after he confessed to approving a blood-
doping plan for a U.S. Nordic skier in 1987 but was reinstated by
the U.S. Skiing Association in 1990.
</P>
<P>
It is still unknown what kind of damages Exum will ask for in
his lawsuit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Cricket to Earn Test Status on June 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is expected to be named
as the tenth Test playing nation of the cricket world on June 26,
The New Nation newpaper reported here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The International Cricket Council (ICC) Board, which will meet
on June 24 to 26, will formally announce their decision on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has already got commitments from eight full members
out of nine in support of its bid for the Test status.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic to get the Test status on June 26 at the
conference of the ICC," President of Bangladesh Cricket Board
Saber Hossain Chowdhury said.
</P>
<P>
India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Zimbabwe and the West Indies backed
Bangladesh at last June's meeting of ICC Board. Three nations,
namely Australia, south Africa and New Zealand, who opposed the
move at that meeting, have already extended their full support to
the country.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, now short of just one vote to earn the Test status,
is seeking the support of England.
</P>
<P>
The president said that after getting the Test status,
Bangladesh would take up a ten-year plan in two phases:
development both at grass-root level and at international level.
</P>
<P>
"Our plan is to go up to fifth or sixth position at world level
in next ten years as well as to hold the World Cup 2011 in
cooperation with India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka," Chowdhury said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
