<HEADLINE> Lakers Help Pay for New Police Cars Damaged in Fans' Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Shaquille O'Neal said
Wednesday that he will pay to replace one of two police cars
torched by rowdy fans celebrating the Los Angeles Lakers' NBA
championship Monday night.
</P>
<P>
"The other night after the game, a couple of bad things
happened, a couple of people trashed two police cars. So on
behalf of the Lakers and (coach) Phil Jackson, we're going to get
them two new police cars," O'Neal told 250,000 Lakers fans, who
turned out Wednesday to celebrate the Lakers' first NBA
Championship since 1988.
</P>
<P>
"We want to say that when we get one (championship) next year,
we just want to be safe, we want everybody to be safe and do the
right thing because we're going to get one next year, too," O'
Neal added.
</P>
<P>
The Lakers and owner Jerry Buss will chip in with Staples
Center to replace the other police vehicle that was burned outside
the arena, Lakers spokesman John Black said Tuesday. Fully
equipped police vehicles can cost around 50,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
A mob looted stores, smashed windows and torched police cars
and news vans outside the arena after the Lakers defeated the
Indiana Pacers 116-111 for the NBA crown. Eleven people were
arrested and four police officers were hurt.
</P>
<P>
Police vowed zero tolerance for parade violence Wednesday and a
highly visible force of more than 300 officers was stationed along
Figueroa Street Staples Center in Downtown Los Angeles to keep the
quarter-million parade peaceful.
</P>
<P>
There were no arrests and no trouble reported. Lakers receive a
hero's welcome Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the Lakers say that O'Neal, the 7-foot-1, 330-
pound center who capped his first championship season by winning
the NBA Finals MVP award, is very active in the community,
particularly in children's programs. He participates in Shaq Paq,
Wish Kids, Shaqsgiving and Shaq-a-Claus. He also is a spokesman
for Reading is Fundamental. 
</P>
