<HEADLINE> ARF Members Agree on DPRK's New Membership: Thai FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan said here Wednesday that the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF)
member countries have agreed on the entry of the Democratic People
's Republic of Korea (DPRK) into the regional security forum.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after attending the third Coordinating
Meeting of the Thailand-Singapore Civil Service Exchange Program (
CSEP) on Wednesday afternoon, Surin also said the ARF has agreed
to invite the DPRK to attend its meeting in July in Bangkok,
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Surin said the ARF members hold unanimous position on the DPRK'
s application for joining the forum, that is, they welcome
Pyongyang's new membership.
</P>
<P>
Surin, currently Chairman of the ARF Standing Committee, said
he received in May the formal application sent by the DPRK's
Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun in an occasion after the DPRK and
South Korea had announced a summit between leaders of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Surin said the DPRK's participation in the ARF is a logical
development as the country will contribute to the region's
stability and security.
</P>
<P>
Set up in 1994 in Bangkok, the ARF comprises the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and other Asian and Pacific rim
nations, including the United States, China, Japan, Canada, Russia,
Papua New Guinea, Mongolia and India. 
</P>
