<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, June 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA -- OPEC approved a deal to lift global oil supply by
three percent, or 708,000 barrels per day (bpd), the cartel's
Secretary-General Rilwanu Lukman announced Wednesday night here.
</P>
<P>
Through the output hike, the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) intended to cool runaway crude oil
prices. Last week, the prices soared to as high as more than 29 U.
S. dollars per barrel and crude futures once jumped to 34 dollars
per barrel in New York market.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, to be effective as from July 1, raises
production limits for those 10 OPEC members, sanctions-bound Iraq
excluded, to 25.4 million bpd from 24.69 million. (Opec-Oil
Output)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand is developing areas in industrial zones to
facilitate new foreign investment projects, which are expected to
significantly increase over the next three years, the Thai News
Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The development of some 8,000 hectares unoccupied industrial
areas will not only lead to new capital inflows, but also revive
the property sector in the country," Staporn Kavit, the Director
of the Board of Investment (BOI), was quoted as saying.(Thailand-
Investment-Facilities)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) leaders
at a regular summit here Wednesday made terms to enhance the
cooperation in the commonwealth and to speed up the progress of
establishing a common free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
CIS leaders approved a joint statement to support international
stability at a closed meeting, Russian President Vladimir Putin's
press service told reporters after today's plenary session of the
CIS Council of Heads of State at the Kremlin. (CIS-Summit-
Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- World Bank President James Wolfensohn on
Wednesday electronically launched the Global Development learning
Network (GDLN), a telecommunications network that connects
distance learning centers in cities across the globe.
</P>
<P>
"What we are participating in today is a result of
technological advances, and another example of globalization at
its best," Wolfensohn said at the launch, and added that "we are
using technology to ensure that everyone has equal access to
knowledge."
</P>
<P>
Via video conferencing, Wolfensohn was joined across many time
zones by leaders from 16 other countries, including China and
France. (World Bank-Network)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The governments of Rwanda and the United States
signed three grant agreements worth 15.1 million U.S. dollars on
Wednesday, bringing the total of U.S. assistance to 485 million
dollars since 1994, Rwanda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Minister of Finance and Economic Planning Donald
Kaberuka and U.S. ambassador to Rwanda George Staples signed the
agreements in the Rwandan capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
The funds granted through the U.S. Agency for International
Development is supposed to be disbursed in the areas of rule of
law and transparency in governance, health and social sector and
food security. (Rwanda-US Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- The German cabinet Wednesday afternoon passed Finance
Minister Hans Eichel's year 2001 budget that aimed to sharply cut
state deficit by sparing the social welfare spending.
</P>
<P>
The bill plans a total spending of 478.7 billion marks (230
billion U.S. dollars 100 million marks less than that of year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The biggest cut lies in jobless help that was directly paid by
the government. Berlin plans to pay 21.1 billion marks as
unemployment help, 1.1 billion less than this year. (Germany-
Budget Bill)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- A total of 56 million homes around the world
will be watching digital TV by the end of this year, a U.S. market
analyst firm reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1999, 34.4 million homes worldwide were watching
digital TV, 77 percent using a direct-to-home satellite service,
21 percent cable and 2 percent terrestrial, according to Strategy
Analytic' report. (Homes-Digital TV)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Visiting Chinese Vice Premier Wen Jiabao Wednesday
urged the entrepreneurs in Britain to invest in China's western
area.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the welcoming luncheon hosted in London by China-
Britain Business Council, Wen said China is implementing the
strategy of large-scale development of China's west, which covers
more than half of the country's total land area.
</P>
<P>
"But in economic development, the west lags far behind other
parts of the country due to historical and other reasons," he said,
adding that the development of the western region will help the
coordinated development of local economy and sustained development
of China's economy as a whole. (UK-China-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Oil production approved Wednesday by the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) will not affect in a
decisive way the international price of the hydrocarbons of
emerging producers like Ecuador, said Wednesday Ecuadorian expert
Jorge Pareja.
</P>
<P>
A production increase of that magnitude does not necessarily
mean a drop in the prices. There can be a reduction of the values,
but not much," of about 0.50 and one dollar per barrel, said
Pareja, insisting that the OPEC decision will not either "clog the
international oil market." (Ecudor-Oil Output-Price)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (
OPEC) agreed Wednesday in Vienna to increase its output by 708,000
barrels a day, so Venezuela can raise its extraction of crude by
81,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
A Petroleos de Venezuela (PDVSA) bulletin says that the
agreement unanimously arrived at by all the OPEC members was to
increase oil output by 708,000 barrels a day, taking as the basis
the production of the last agreement this same year.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela can increase its production by 81,000 barrels a day,
so its total output will be three million barrels a day. (
Venezuela-Oil Output) 
</P>
