<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Thailand Meet for Cooperation in Disease Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- A preparatory meeting for Myanmar-
Thailand inter-country cooperation in disease control is underway
here to select issues to be discussed at the upcoming meeting
between the health ministries of the two countries scheduled for
July 7-9.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting is attended by health officials of Myanmar
and Thailand including district doctors from border regions of the
two countries and representatives of the World Health Organization
(WHO) .
</P>
<P>
There are three areas for cooperation in the disease control
between Myanmar and Thailand, namely malaria, tuberculosis (TB)
and HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the meeting on Wednesday,
Myanmar Minister of Health Major-General Ket Sein said the
patterns of disease transmission and underlying causes of diseases
are similar in both Myanmar and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He called for learning from respective countries' situation and
experiences so as to identify ways to enhance inter-country
collaboration between the two countries in the prevention and
control of these diseases.
</P>
<P>
He elaborated that Myanmar has fought against these diseases as
a national concern and prioritized programs within the framework
of the country's national health plan, saying that the two
countries have conducted five very important border meetings on
malaria in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that twin malaria clinics have already been
established at many strategic cross-border points with
synchronized studies on Therapeutic Efficacy of anti-malaria drugs
also conducted by both countries at the Tachilek (Myanmar)-Maesai
(Thailand) areas.
</P>
<P>
Exchange of information on epidemics has also been carried out
by Myanmar and Thailand, he said, adding that joint activities on
information, education and communication campaign were conducted
in three major border points during the past few years.
</P>
<P>
He went on saying that TB has been identified as one of the
major priority diseases in Myanmar's national health plan and the
national TB control program has covered 223 townships out of 324
in the country in carrying out WHO-recommended short course
chemotherapy known as Directly Observed Treatment Short Course (
DOTS) which is planned to be implemented in the entire country by
the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
He gave an account that country-wide activities such as
National Malaria Week, National TB Control Day and World AIDS Day
have been observed to promote community awareness.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Myanmar can collaborate with Thailand in many
areas of TB control, prevention and care such as sharing of best
practices, research on drug resistance patterns and the efficacy
of indigenous drugs and so on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
