<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Approves 3 Percent Output Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- OPEC approved a deal to lift global
oil supply by three percent, or 708,000 barrels per day (bpd), the
cartel's Secretary-General Rilwanu Lukman announced Wednesday
night here.
</P>
<P>
Through the output hike, the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) intended to cool runaway crude oil
prices. Last week, the prices soared to as high as more than 29 U.
S. dollars per barrel and crude futures once jumped to 34 dollars
per barrel in New York market.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, to be effective as from July 1, raises
production limits for those 10 OPEC members, sanctions-bound Iraq
excluded, to 25.4 million bpd from 24.69 million.
</P>
<P>
Lukman said that OPEC will do whatever it takes to bring prices
down to a reasonable level, which it puts at 25 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting in March, the cartel had decided that once
crude prices run out of the range of 22 to 28 dollars per barrel
for more than 20 days, it will cut or lift output limits by 500,
000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
So OPEC's move came as predicted since the prices had jumped
over the upper limit of 28 dollars per barrel starting from mid-
May.
</P>
<P>
The United States welcomed OPEC's decision. "I am pleased with
this figure and hopefully, with additional oil from non-OPEC
countries that might be announced soon, that this will be good
news for the American consumer," Reuters quoted U.S. Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson as saying.
</P>
<P>
In early March, under pressure from consumer governments, OPEC
agreed to a seven percent rise in group output in the second
quarter to 24.69 million bpd and the oil price started going down
from its nine-year peak. But the relief did not last long and the
prices again soared over the 30-dollar mark as the peak summer
driving season came.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts here are skeptical that the price will be
cooled down following Wednesday's decision. It is said that before
the agreement, OPEC countries had already increased its output by
500,000 bpd, therefore on July 1 the world market will see but an
extra supply of 200,000 bpd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000622.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
