<HEADLINE> British Swim Coach Detained in Drug Smuggling Crackdown in Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Spanish police had arrested four
people, including British swimming coach Cecil Russell, during a
crackdown on the smuggling of Ecstasy tablets into the United
States, a police statement said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Russell, now training former Russian swimmer
Nina Jivanevskaia, was detained earlier this week along with three
others in the southern Spanish city of Torremolinos.
</P>
<P>
When Russell was arrested at the Olympic swimming pool in
Torremolinos, police seized 513 Ecstasy tablets hidden in ceramic
figurines that were to be mailed to the United States,said police.
</P>
<P>
Jivanevskaia who obtained Spanish residency about a year ago,
is a favorite in the upcoming Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 Russell was banned for life from coaching swimming in
the United States and Canada after he was accused of supplying and
selling anabolic steroids. He was coaching at the Fort Lauderdale
(Florida) Swim Team at the time.
</P>
<P>
Spanish news agnecy EFE said the arrests were part of a
crackdown, coordinated with the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency, on a
smuggling ring that had sent 9,000 ecstasy pills to the United
States through Dutch and Spanish postal services. 
</P>
