<HEADLINE> World's Longest Epic Renascent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Tibetan heroic epic "Life of King
Gesar", the world's longest epic, has regained its golden time,
with a total of print run of over three million copies.
</P>
<P>
"This epic, which has for long centuries been known only to a
few folk artists, has come out as a systematically complete
literary masterpiece that is called 'the king of world epics'",
said the White Paper entitled "The Development of Tibetan Culture"
issued by the Information Office of the State Council here today.
</P>
<P>
The world-famous "Life of King Gesar", a rare literary treasure
of China and the whole of mankind, has all along been passed down
by folk artists orally.
</P>
<P>
To better protect it, the Tibet Autonomous Region in southwest
China set up special bodies in 1979 for the collection, research,
editing ad publishing of the epic. The state placed it on the key
scientific research project lists of the Sixth, Seventh and Eighth
Five-Year Plans.
</P>
<P>
The White Paper said that after 20 years of effort, nearly 300
handwritten or block-printed Tibetan volumes of the epic have been
collected. Among them, except 100 variant volumes, about 70
volumes have been formally published in the Tibetan language, with
a total print run of well over three million copies, which was an
unprecedented achievement in protecting the Tibetan literary and
art heritage, as well as in publishing history.
</P>
<P>
This is only one tip of the iceberg, and the regional
authorities have always attached importance to the inheritance and
development of Tibetan culture and art.
</P>
<P>
The White Paper said that as early as in the 1950s, literary
and art workers collected music, dance, folk stories, proverbs ad
folk songs and published some books including "Tibetan Folk Songs".
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, the regional government has assigned survey
teams to make extensive investigation and collection of literary
and art heritage and these efforts resulted in the collection of
some 30 million words of written materials and the publication of
a large amount of video tapes, pictures and books.
</P>
<P>
The White Paper said that a series of collections of Tibetan
ballads, folk songs, opera music and folk stories are now under
compilation and will be published soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
