<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Philippine Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Philippine newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Manila Bulletin:
</P>
<P>
-- Philippine Bureau of Immigration has entered into a covenant
with 12 other government agencies for an intensified campaign
against trafficking, including the arrest, prosecution, and
conviction of members of human smuggling syndicates.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Daily Inquirer:
</P>
<P>
-- The rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front is down from 46
camps to only two major camps -- Abubakar and Rajamuda -- and
seven satellite camps serving as defense perimeters, the Armed
Forces of the Philippines declared Wednesday in Manila.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star:
</P>
<P>
-- Officials of Finland, France and Germany vowed Wednesday
that they will not be paying any ransom for the release of their
nationals who are among the 21 hostages being held by the
extremist Abu Sayyaf in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Malaya:
</P>
<P>
-- Philippine President Joseph Estrada said Wednesday
government will intensify military offensives against the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front after June 30 if the rebel group refuses
to abandon its secessionist move and stop terrorist activities.
</P>
