<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, June 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's leftist party Meretz decided Wednesday to
quit Prime Minister Ehud Barak's coalition government in what it
called an effort to further Barak's peacemaking with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Three Meretz cabinet ministers will tender their resignations
to Barak later Wednesday after the party's 10 Knesset (parliament)
members met and made the decision earlier, according to Israel
Television. (Israel-Coalition-Meretz)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Wednesday okayed a
12-month extension of the Stabilization Force in Bosnia (SFOR) and
a U.N. mission there, and Russia Wednesday abstained from the
Council vote in protest against the exclusion of Yugoslavia from
an international conference last month on the future of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation Council voted 14-0 for a resolution to renew the
21,000-strong SFOR and the U.N. mission comprising 1,600 police.
(UN-Bosnia-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Sierra Leone rebels have re-taken the strategic town
of Lunsar from pro-government forces, according to a report from
the war-torn West African country Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted U.N. military spokesman Lieutenant Commander
Patrick Coker as saying in capital Freetown that "the information
we have is that Lunsar is under the control of the Revolutionary
United Front." SLeone-Rebels-Strategic Town
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council and the Economic
Community of the West African Countries (ECOWAS) here Wednesday
voiced their condemnation of the rebel's "continued detention" of
U.N. peacekeepers in Sierra Leone, and demanded the "immediate and
unconditional release of all United Nations personnel detained or
surrounded."
</P>
<P>
The condemnation was contained in a joint statement read to
the press by the president of the Security Council, Jean-David
Levitte, at the end of the day-long meeting with an ECOWAS
delegation behind closed doors.  (UN-Sierra Leone-Rebels)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW-- A top Russian military officer warned here Wednesday
that his country may withdraw from the Medium-Range Missile Treaty
and resume the development of medium and medium-short range
missiles If the U.S. builds missile defense systems.
</P>
<P>
Russia will strongly react to the deployment of the U.S.
national missile defense (NMD) system, said Col. Gen. Vladimir
Yakovlev, Commander-in-Chief of the Russian Strategic Missile
Force (SMF) at a news briefing. (Russia-US-ABM)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The position of the Council of Europe (COE) on the
Cyprus issue has never changed and it recognizes the sole entity
on the island, the Republic of Cyprus and its government, said a
visiting COE official. (Cyprus-COE )
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Pierre Schori, head of the European Union (EU)
election observer team to Zimbabwe, Wednesday condemned the on-
going political violence in the country, and urged Zimbabweans to
vote for parties of their own choice.
</P>
<P>
Schori, who is in Bulawayo, the country's second largest city,
to get first hand information on the political situation in the
city and surrounding areas, told the Zimbabwe News Agency that
violence and intimidation had no place in any democratic election.
(Zimbabwe-EU-Violence)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- The Organization of African Unity (OAU) has sent
an observer team to Zimbabwe to monitor the country's
parliamentary elections to be held from June 24 to 25.
</P>
<P>
The 20-member team, headed by Liberian former president Amos
Sawyer, consists of diplomats, lawyers, human rights workers,
representatives of women organizations and the OAU General
Secretariat. (OAU-Zimbabwe-Observation) 
</P>
</TEXT>
