<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wilkens Named Coach of Toronto Raptors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Lenny Wilkens, who has the most
coaching wins in National Basketball Association history,
announced Wednesday that he will take the helm of the Toronto
Raptors.
</P>
<P>
The Raptors, who made the play-offs last season for the first
time in its five-year history, are hoping the 62-year-old Wilkens
can build the young squad into a legitimate contender.
</P>
<P>
Regarded as a "players coach", Wilkens brings to Toronto a 1,
179-981 win-loss record including a 310-232 record in seven years
with the Atlanta Hawks. He has also coached in Portland, Seattle
and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
Toronto's general manager Glen Grunwald signed Wilkens to a
four-year contract reportedly worth of 20 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Wilkens resigned from his post with the Hawks in April after
the worst season of his 27-year coaching career, which saw the
team post a 28-54 record last season. He had two years remaining
on his contract with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Wilkens is in the Basketball Hall of Fame as a player and a
coach, making him the only double inductee from the NBA. He was
also voted to the list of the NBA's 50 Greatest Players in 1996
and later named one of the NBA's 10 Greatest Coaches.
</P>
<P>
Raptors' former coach Butch Carter was sacked last week largely
because of his feuding with players. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
