<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stock Markets End Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Europe's leading stock markets all
ended lower Thursday as drug and technology shares fell back which
outnumbered gainers in a three-to-two majority.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 fell for a second day, as telecom stocks
declined and a weaker opening on Wall Street undermined investor
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark index ended 64.0 points or 0.99 percent lower at
6413.8, slipping back in the last hour of trade following a weak
start on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Pharmaceuticals sector sentiment was hit by a sharp fall in
Swiss drug company Roche after it warned of low,single-digit first-
half drug sales growth due to weak US prescription sales.
</P>
<P>
Glaxo Wellcome was 2.1 percent lower, Smithkline Beecham
declined two percent and the sector as a whole knocked 14 points
off the FTSE.
</P>
<P>
BP Amoco gained 1.3 percent after OPEC's agreement to raise
world crude supplies by a lower-than-expected three percent or a
daily increment of 708.000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt's Xetra Dax, lacking an oil component, spent the
entire session in the red and was 0.82 percent lower at 7042.03 at
the close of business in London and Paris.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 in Paris closed 0.24 percent lower at 6474.8 having
spent most of the session in the black before declines in
industrial and drug shares dragged it to a lower close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
