<HEADLINE> Italy Funds 5.7 Billions Dollars For South, Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government Thursday
announced funding of 12 trillion lire (about 5.7 billion U.S.
dollars) for the south, as well as transport and public services
in a move that Treasury Minister Vincenzo Visco said should help
the south grow faster than the north.
</P>
<P>
"Expenditure will rise, the South's development will grow and
unemployment will fall in these areas in the next few years," said
Visco.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, regional growth figures issued by Istat, the
Italian national statistics institute, indicated that in the first
quarter of the year, southern growth was already racing away at 23.
2 percent, compared to 17.5 percent for the north.
</P>
<P>
The new funding will go to the South's development program for
2000-2006 to get some halted projects going again, to improve some
local development programs and finance new subway lines and
railway modernization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
