<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Nigerian Leader Receives Africa Peace Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Former Nigerian head of state
General Abdul Salam Abubaker on Thursday evening received the
Africa Peace Award for his major role in bringing peace and
stability to his country.
</P>
<P>
Abubaker, who took power after the military ruler Sani Abacha
died in 1998, voluntarily ceded power to the elected President
Olusegun Obasanjo in May 1999, ending 15-year military rule in
Africa's most populous country.
</P>
<P>
The award was handed to Abubaker at a ceremony on the second
day of the three-day Southern African Economic Summit in Durban,
South Africa, sponsored by the World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
The prestigious award presented for every two years since 1993
has been billed "Africa's Nobel Peace Prize".
</P>
<P>
The award was the initiative of the African Centre for
Constructive Resolution of Disputes (ACCROD).
</P>
<P>
ACCROD executive director Vaso Gounden said the change brought
about in Nigeria by Abubaker's commitment to peace made a
remarkable impact on the whole of the African continent.
</P>
<P>
The past winners included the Kwazulu-Natal community of
Mpumalanga for peace efforts between the Inkatha Freedom Party
and the African National Congress (1993), Mozambique (1997) and
former South African president Nelson Mandela (1995).
</P>
<P>
The winners of the Africa Peace Award are chosen according to a
strict set of principles: commitment to human rights, the peaceful
settlement of disputes and good governance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
