<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Environment Minister Suspended From Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Environment and Natural
Resources Minster Ben Mwila was suspended from the ruling Movement
for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD) Thursday for violating party
regulations.
</P>
<P>
Mwila, who is also National Treasurer of the ruling party, has
been given 10 days to exculpate himself, said a disciplinary
letter dated June 22 signed by MMD National Secretary Michael
Sata.
</P>
<P>
In the letter Sata charged that in the past 18 months, Mwila
has been involved in anti-party activities that has greatly
destabilized the party.
</P>
<P>
Mwila provoked the party leadership by announcing his
candidature for the MMD presidency on May 26 as the first step to
run for the country's president in the 2001 general elections.
</P>
<P>
But incumbent President and MMD leader Frederick Chiluba, whose
second and last five-year term will expire in 2001, has indicated
that he will ensure that Mwila does not become the president and
MMD has said it is not the time to start the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Mwila, one of the country's richest businessmen, helped Chiluba
defeat former President Kenneth Kaunda in the 1991 elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
