<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia, U.S. Sign Agreement on Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Georgian Defense Minister David
Tevnadze and deputy chief of the U.S. Defense Department Edward
Warner signed Thursday in Tbilisi an agreement on U.S. offering
great military aid for Georgia's accession to NATO, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is paying great attention to the process of the
Georgian army formation, and Georgia will receive considerable
help in this sphere, Warner told a news conference after the
accord was signed in Tbilisi, capital of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Georgia's Armed Forces will gradually meet the standards for a
membership of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in
three-five years, as the former Soviet republic is now past its
initial stage of fundamental military reforms and will comply with
NATO's military standards step by step, said Warner.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze said
after his re-election as head of state that his country will
strive for joining the North Atlantic alliance by 2005 when his
mandate expires.
</P>
<P>
However, Warner said the achievement of this objective will to
a great extent depend on Georgia's economic possibilities. He said
the U.S. is ready to render all sorts of help to the Georgian army,
but the Georgian government will have to solve specific problems.
</P>
<P>
Edward Warner told journalists that Washington intends to
consider helping Tbilisi establish a modern air defense system,
utilize and export military waste.
</P>
<P>
Warner's visit to Georgia will end Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
