<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in L.America Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Latin America and the Caribbean
received a little over 4 billion U.S. dollars in direct foreign
investment in the 1990s, which shows the growing importance the
region has gained as a platform for foreign investments, according
to a bulletin distributed Thursday here by the Latin American
Economic System (SELA).
</P>
<P>
The bulletin says that nowadays, direct foreign investing is
considered a key piece for financing the development of countries
and their insertion in the globalizing process, hence the
governments' interest to articulate their participation within
their national development strategies.
</P>
<P>
This matter will be object of wide analysis within the
framework of "Foreign Investments in Latin America and the
Caribbean: Experiences and Perspectives" forum, which will take
place in Caracas on June 29 and 30, convoked by the Permanent
Secretariat of Latin America's Permanent Secretariat (SELA).
</P>
<P>
According to figures by Spain's Ministry of Economy and
Treasury, in these years, annual flows of Spain's direct investing
to the region went from 780 million dollars to 12.6 billion
dollars, concentrating on oil, telecommunication, banking and
electric energy sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
