<HEADLINE> Tension Between Ecuadoran Government, Unions Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Tension between Ecuador's
government and teachers on strike increased following surprising
detention of a teachers' union president, Aracelly Moreno,
Wednesday evening by police members.
</P>
<P>
The director of the National Union of Educators (UNE) is in
jail at Quito's Judicial Technical Police offices. There lay upon
her a preventive police order for not respecting Ecuador's
constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
Some 142,000 public school and college teachers from all over
the country belonging to the UNE continued Thursday their stoppage
which began on May 15, insisting on their petition of a basic wage
increase to at least 100 U.S. dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
According to UNE leaders, Aracelly Moreno was held for 48 hours
to be investigated in a slander trial against the Republic's
President, Gustavo Noboa, at the Pichincha prison's third court.
</P>
<P>
Aracelly Moreno had confirmed that leader Noboa and his
brothers would benefit from the restructuring of debts above 50,
000 dollars and because of this, it was necessary to shut popular
leaders' voices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
