<HEADLINE> Peru, Mercosur Trade Over 320 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Peru and Southern
Common Market (Mercosur) member countries reached over 320 million
U.S. dollars during year 2000's first four months, Peru's Foreign
Ministry's Economic Projection Office (OPE) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Brazil keeps on being Peru's main
trading partner because during this period trade between both
sides reached 191.35 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Argentina came in second place with a trade value of 123.84
million dollars, followed by Uruguay with 22.59 million dollars,
and Paraguay with 4.45 million.
</P>
<P>
Peru's exports to Mercosur reached 83.94 million dollars, while
imports from that regional bloc went up to 245.56 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The OPE's report said that Peru's main export products were
mineral and zinc extracts, fresh asparagus, flour and fish
preserves.
</P>
<P>
Peru's imports coming from Mercosur are made up mainly by wheat
and certain by-products, diverse domestic electric devices,
dressing articles and food products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
