<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Unveils Plans for Web-Based Software Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft unveiled Thursday
the vision for its next generation of software and services, aimed
at making its existing software available over the Web to
traditional PCs and to new devices such as cell phone and personal
digital assistants.
</P>
<P>
Capitalizing on the explosion of Internet-based computing and
communications, the new set of products and services, under the
umbrella name Microsoft.Net, will provide easier, more
personalized and more productive Internet experiences by
harnessing constellations of small devices and Web sites with
advanced software through Internet protocols and formats.
</P>
<P>
The new initiative is part of Microsoft's goal of keeping
Windows the dominant operating system, even as computing begins to
move from desktop PCs toward Internet-enabled wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft chairman Bill Gates said that the goal of the plan is
to connect every computing device and tie them to the Internet.
All data will be synchronized, allowing consumers and workers to
access the Internet, e-mail, calendars and important files,
regardless of what device they're using.
</P>
<P>
"The impact of the Internet has been spectacular to date, but
the pace of innovation will accelerate over the next five years,"
Gates said. "Our goal is to move beyond today's world of
standalone Web sites to an Internet of interchangeable components
where devices and services can be assembled into cohesive, user-
driven experience."
</P>
<P>
He said that "we have an opportunity to take this vision," but
his company faces a field of competitors such as IBM and Sun
Microsystems who have been pushing similar software-as-service
platforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
