<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile's Copper Exports Go Up 3.2 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Chile's copper exports registered
a 3.2 percent growth during year 2000's first quarter compared
with 1999's same period, Chile's Copper Commission (COCHILCO)
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Between January and March, 1.069 million tons of copper were
exported, representing an increase of 32.8 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In its report, COCHILCO indicated that income for exports went
up 33.9 percent with regard to 1999, which can be basically
explained by the rise in the metal's average price.
</P>
<P>
During 1999's first six-month period, copper exports reached a
value of 308.4 million U.S. dollars and in year 2000, income went
up to 1.571 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
As regards destinations of copper exports, Asia comes in first
place with 47.3 percent of Chile's exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
