<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Approves 300 Million Dollars in Loan to Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 22 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) announced Thursday the approval of a loan of 300
million U.S. dollars to Mexico to expand the supply of credit to
small and medium-sized businesses and to enhance the
competitiveness and technological capacity of the financial and
business sectors.
</P>
<P>
For the credit component of the program, Nacional Financiera, S.
N.C. (NAFIN) will onlend funds to financial intermediaries that in
turn will provide credit to private enterprises, the Washington-
based IDB said.
</P>
<P>
Subloans for an average of 150,000 dollars each will be made
available to at least 3,900 businesses in all areas of the economy,
both urban and rural.
</P>
<P>
An eight-million-dollar technical assistance component of the
program will help NAFIN, the financial intermediaries, and small
and medium-sized businesses enhance their credit and services
technologies and become more competitive.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is 600 million dollars. The IDB
loan from its U.S. Dollar Window is for a 12-year term, with a
five-year grace period and a three-year disbursement period, at a
variable interest rate that will be fixed at the moment of each
disbursement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
